  url "https://en.wiktionary.org/w/api.php?action=parse&page=ade&prop=wikitext&formatversion=2&format=json&redirects=1"
  body "{""parse"":{""title"":""ade"",""pageid"":576359,""redirects"":[],""wikitext"":""{{also|Appendix:Variations of \""ade\""}}\n==Translingual==\n\n===Symbol===\n{{mul-symbol}}\n\n# {{ISO 639|3}}\n\n===See also===\n* {{l"
  body "angcat}}\n\n==English==\n\n===Etymology===\n{{back-form|en|lemonade}}, {{m|en|orangeade}}, etc.\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{IPA|en|/ˈeɪd/}}\n* {{audio|en|LL-Q1860 (eng)-Flame, not lame-ade.wav|a=US}}\"
  body "n* {{rhymes|en|eɪd|s=1}}\n* {{homophone|en|aid|aide}}\n\n===Noun===\n{{en-noun}}\n\n# A [[drink]] made from a [[fruit]], especially a [[fizzy]] one.\n#: {{syn|en|fruitade}}\n#* {{quote-text|en|year=18"
  body "95|author=John G Bourke|title=Folk-foods of the Rio Grande Valley of Northern Mexico|page=61|passage=To come to the tables or stands: they were loaded with chocolate, coffee, agua de miel, pulque, mes"
  body "cal, orchatas of several kinds, all the lemon and other \""'''ades'''\"" already described, as well as all the cakes and candies, {{...}}}}\n#* {{quote-text|en|year=1905|title=American Bottler|volume=25"
  body "|page=74\n|passage=If the judgment of the above-mentioned office be correct, in truth, no drink may here be offered to the public as lemonade unless it is made out of fresh fruit! And so with raspberr"
  body "yade and all the other \""'''ades'''.\""}}\n\n====Derived terms====\n{{col|en|grapefruitade}}\n\n====Translations====\n{{trans-top|drink made from a fruit}}\n* Chinese:\n*: Mandarin: {{t+|cmn|泡泡|tr=pàop"
  body "ào}}, {{t+|cmn|果汁|tr=guǒzhī}}\n* Dutch: {{t+|nl|limonade|f}}, {{t+|nl|priklimonade|f}}, {{t+|nl|frisdrank|m}}\n* Finnish: {{t+|fi|limu}} {{q|fizzy}}; {{t|fi|hedelmäjuoma}}\n* Japanese: {{t|ja|エード|tr=ē"
  body "do}}\n* Korean: {{t|ko|에이드}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n===Anagrams===\n* {{anagrams|en|a=ade|Eda|'ead|DAE|EAD|DEA|EDA|AED}}\n\n{{topics|en|Beverages}}\n\n==Bangka==\n\n===Alternative forms===\n* {{alt|mfb|"
  body "ado<qq:Belinyu dialect>}}\n\n===Etymology===\nFrom {{inh|mfb|poz-mly-pro|*ada(ʔ)}}, from {{der|mfb|poz-pro|*wada}}. Cognate of {{cog|ms|ada}}.\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{IPA|mfb|/ˈade/|/ˈadə/}}\n\n=="
  body "=Verb===\n{{head|mfb|v|head=adè|head2=adê}}\n\n# to [[be]] {{gloss|exist}}\n#: {{ant|mfb|dakde}}\n#: {{usex|mfb|'''Ade''' due telok ayam.|'''There are''' two chicken eggs.}}\n# to [[have]]\n#: {{syn|m"
  body "fb|punye}}\n#: {{ant|mfb|dakde|dak}}\n#: {{usex|mfb|Aku '''ade''' buku baru|I '''have''' a new book.}}\n\n===Further reading===\n* {{R:mfb:Susilo 2018}}\n\n==Esperanto==\n\n===Etymology===\n{{etymon|e"
  body "o|:af|-ad-|-e}}\nFrom {{suffix|eo|-ad-|-e}}.\n\n===Pronunciation===\n{{eo-pr|a=LL-Q143 (epo)-Lepticed7-ade.wav;LL-Q143 (epo)-Robin van der Vliet-ade.wav}}\n\n===Adverb===\n{{eo-head}}\n\n# [[continual"
  body "ly]], [[permanently]], [[consistently]]\n\n===Further reading===\n* {{R:eo:PIV 2020}}\n\n==Ewe==\n{{number box|ee}}\n\n===Etymology===\n{{rfe|ee}}\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{ee-IPA|àdé}}\n\n===Numera"
  body "l===\n{{ee-number|àdé}}\n\n# [[six]]\n\n===References===\n* {{R:ee:Basic Ewe|19}}\n* {{R:ee:Nuseline|7}}\n\n==Garo==\n\n===Etymology===\nClipping of {{l|grt|ma·de}}\n\n===Noun===\n{{head|grt|noun}}\n\"
  body "n# [[younger]] [[maternal aunt]]\n\n====Synonyms====\n* {{l|grt|ma·degipa}} {{qualifier|formal}}\n* {{l|grt|ma·detang}} {{qualifier|formal}}\n* {{l|grt|ma·de}}\n\n{{C|grt|Female family members}}\n\n=="
  body "German==\n\n===Etymology===\nFrom {{inh|de|gmh|adē}}, from {{der|de|fro|adieu}}. {{doublet|de|tschö}}.\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{IPA|de|/aˈdeː/}}\n* {{rhymes|de|eː|s=2}}\n* {{audio|de|De-Ade.ogg}}\n"
  body "* {{audio|de|De-ade.ogg|a=<<Germany>> (<<Berlin>>)}}\n\n===Interjection===\n{{head|de|interjection}}\n\n# {{lb|de|archaic|poetic|or|regional}} [[farewell]], [[adieu]]\n\n===Further reading===\n* {{R:d"
  body "e:Duden}}\n* {{R:de:DWDS}}\n\n{{cln|de|farewells}}\n\n==Guanche==\n\n===Noun===\n{{head|gnc|noun}}\n\n# [[water]]\n\n===References===\n* Juan Álvarez Delgado, ''Miscelánea guanche : I. Benahoare : ens"
  body "ayos de lingüística canaria'', 1942\n\n==Lindu==\n\n===Noun===\n{{head|klw|noun}}\n\n# {{lb|klw|anatomy}} [[chin]]\n\n==Macanese==\n\n===Etymology===\nFrom {{der|mzs|roa-opt|ãade|t=duck; mallard}}, po"
  body "ssibly via a de-nasalized variant of {{der|mzs|pt|adem|t=mallard}}.\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{IPA|mzs|/ˈa.di/}}\n\n===Noun===\n{{head|mzs|noun}}\n\n# [[duck]]\n#: {{coi|mzs|'''ade''' salgado|t='''du"
  body "ck''' salted in brine}}\n#: {{coi|mzs|'''ade'''-cabidela|t=''stew made with duck and duck blood''}}\n#: {{coi|mzs|voz di '''ade'''-macho|t=hoarse/husky voice|lit=voice of male '''duck'''}}\n\n====Usag"
  body "e notes====\n* Macanese makes a distinction between {{m|mzs|ade|t=duck}} and {{m|mzs|pato|t=drake}}. This distinction is obsolete in Portugal.\n\n====Derived terms====\n* {{l|mzs|bafo di ade}}\n\n===R"
  body "eferences===\n* https://www.macaneselibrary.org/pub/english/uipatua.htm#ade\n* https://www.macaneselibrary.org/pub/english/uipatua.htm#f_ade\n\n{{C|mzs|Ducks|Poultry}}\n\n==Northern Kurdish==\n\n===Et"
  body "ymology 1===\n{{rfe|kmr}}\n\n====Alternative forms====\n* {{alter|kmr|ede|'ede|ادا}}\n\n====Pronunciation====\n* {{kmr-IPA}}\n\n====Noun====\n{{kmr-noun|m|ar=ئادە}}\n\n# [[weed]] {{gl|unwanted plant}}"
  body "\n\n=====Declension=====\n{{kmr-decl-noun|m}}\n\n=====Derived terms=====\n* {{l|kmr|ade kirin}}\n\n===Etymology 2===\n\n====Pronunciation====\n* {{kmr-IPA}}\n\n====Noun====\n{{kmr-noun|f|ar=ئادە}}\n\n"
  body "# {{altform|kmr|ada|t=island}}\n\n=====Declension=====\n{{kmr-decl-noun|f}}\n\n===References===\n* {{R:kmr:Chyet:2020|ada I|vol=1|page=1}}\n* {{R:kmr:Chyet:2020|ada II|vol=1|page=2}}\n\n{{C|kmr|Plants"
  body "}}\n\n==Wiwa==\n\n===Noun===\n{{head|mbp|noun}}\n\n# [[father]]\n#: ranže ade terga\n#:: my father is in the field\n\n===References===\n* ''The Languages of the Andes'' (2004, Willem F. H. Adelaar, Pi"
  body "eter C. Muysken)<!--citing Trillos Amaya 2000)-->\n\n==Wolio==\n\n===Etymology===\nFrom {{inh|wlo|poz-pro|*qazay}}.\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{IPA|wlo|/aɗe/}}\n\n===Noun===\n{{head|wlo|noun}}\n\n# [["
  body "chin]]\n\n===References===\n* Anceaux, Johannes C. 1987. ''Wolio Dictionary (Wolio-English-Indonesian) / Kamus Bahasa Wolio (Wolio-Inggeris-Indonesia).'' Dordrecht: Foris.\n\n==Yoruba==\n[[File:Brookl"
  body "yn Museum 70.109.1a-b Beaded Crown Ade of Onijagbo Obasoro Alowolodu Ogoga of Ikere 1890-1928 (2).jpg|thumb|'''Adé''' láti Ikẹ́rẹ́]]\n\n===Etymology===\nFrom {{affix|yo|a-|dé|t1=agent prefix|id1=agent"
  body " prefix|t2=to wear on the head, to cap, to crown|lit=that which is worn on the head}}.\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{yo-IPA|adé}}\n\n===Noun===\n{{yo-noun|adé}}\n\n# [[crown]]\n# {{lb|yo|by extension}} "
  body "[[royalty]]\n# A [[common]] [[prefix]] in Yoruba [[given]] [[names]] and [[surnames]] for those born in [[royalty]]\n# the [[top]] [[part]] of [[something]]\n## the [[top]] [[part]] of a [[tree]]\n\n="
  body "===Derived terms====\n{{col2|yo\n|aládé<t:prince, princess, royal>\n|Adébáyọ̀<pos:Yoruba name><lit:Royalty meets joy>\n|Adéyanjú<pos:Yoruba name><lit:The crown is complete>\n|Adéṣidà<pos:Yoruba name><"
  body "lit:The crown has not broken any taboos>\n|Adébọ́rọ̀<pos:Yoruba name><lit:Royalty meets wealth>\n}}\n\n==Zaghawa==\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{IPA|zag|/ʔadɛ/}}\n\n===Noun===\n{{head|zag|noun}}\n\n# [["
  body "beard]]\n\n===References===\n* ''[https://web.archive.org/web/20230314181521/http://www.tchad.org/zaghawa/Beria-Eng-BDict.pdf Beria-English English-Beria Dictionary] [provisional] ADESK, Iriba, Kobe D"
  body "epartment, Chad''""}}"

response_0005_api_php_action_parse_pag
  url "https://en.wiktionary.org/w/api.php?action=parse&page=and&prop=wikitext&formatversion=2&format=json&redirects=1"
  body "{""parse"":{""title"":""and"",""pageid"":2067,""redirects"":[],""wikitext"":""{{also|Appendix:Variations of \""and\""}}\n{{minitoc}}\n==Translingual==\n\n===Etymology===\n{{clip|mul|en:'''An'''sus}} with {{m|mul|d}}"
  body " as a placeholder.\n\n===Symbol===\n{{mul-symbol}}\n\n# {{ISO 639|3}}\n\n===See also===\n* {{langcat}}\n\n==English==\n{{wp}}\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{a|en|stressed}}\n** {{IPA|en|/ˈænd/|[ˈænd]|a=n"
  body "on-æ-raising}}\n*** {{audio|en|LL-Q1860 (eng)-Pvanp7-and (stressed).wav|a=UK}}\n** {{a|en|æ-raising}}\n*** {{IPA|en|/ˈeə̯nd/|[ˈeə̯nd]|;|/ˈɛə̯nd/|[ˈɛə̯nd]|a=US,CA}}\n**** {{audio|en|en-us-and.ogg|a=US}"
  body "}\n* {{IPA|en|/ˈənd/|[ˈənd]|;|[n̩d]|;|[n̩ʔ]|a=unstressed}}\n** {{audio|en|LL-Q1860 (eng)-Pvanp7-and (unstressed).wav|a=UK}}\n** {{audio|en|LL-Q1860 (eng)-Vealhurl-and (unstressed).wav|a=Southern Engla"
  body "nd}}\n** {{audio|en|en-us-ham-and-eggs.ogg|a=US|text=ham and eggs|IPA=/ˈhɛə̯m‿n̩‿ɛɡz/}}\n* {{rhymes|en|ænd|s=1}}<!-- NOTE: Do not add /ənd/, /ən/, etc. rhymes: no rhymes with an unstressed word.-->\n*"
  body " {{hyph|en|and}}\n* {{hmp|en|an<qq:unstressed>|ant<qq:in some accents>|end<qq:in some accents>|in<qq:unstressed>}}\n\n===Etymology 1===\n{{etymon|en|id=conjunction|:inh|enm:and<id:conjunction>|tree=1}"
  body "}\n{{root|en|ine-pro|*h₂en-}}\n{{inh+|en|enm|and}}, {{m|enm|an}}, from {{inh|en|ang|and}}, {{m|ang|ond}}, {{m|ang|end}}, from {{inh|en|gmw-pro|*andi}}, from {{inh|en|gem-pro|*andi}}, {{m|gem-pro|*anþi"
  body "}}, from {{inh|en|ine-pro|*h₂énti||facing opposite, near, in front of, before}}. Cognate with {{cog|sco|an||and}}, {{cog|frr|än||and}}, {{cog|stq|un||and}}, {{cog|fy|en||and}}, {{cog|nl|en}}, {{m|nl|e"
  body "nde||and}}, {{cog|de|und||and}}, {{cog|nds-de|on}}, {{m|nds-de|un||and}}, {{cog|lb|an||and}}, {{cog|wym|an}}, {{m|wym|ana||and}}, {{cog|yi|און}}, {{m|yi|אונ}}, {{m|yi|אונד}}, {{m|yi|אונ׳||and}}, {{cog"
  body "|da|end||still; ever; even}}, {{cog|fo|enn||still, yet}}, {{cog|is|en||and}}, {{m|is|enn||still, yet}}, {{cog|nb|enn||and}}, {{cog|nn|en}}, {{m|nn|enn||and}}, {{cog|sv|än||still, yet}}, {{cog|sq|edhe|"
  body "|and}} (dialectal {{m|sq|[[ênde]], [[ênne]]}}), {{m|sq|ende||still, yet, therefore}}, {{cog|la|ante||opposite, in front of}}, {{cog|grc|ἀντί||opposite, facing}}. {{doublet|en|an}} (\""if\"").\n\n====Alt"
  body "ernative forms====\n* {{l|en|an'}}\n* {{l|en|'n'}} ({{l|en|n}})\n\n====Conjunction====\n{{en-head|conj}}\n\n# As a coordinating conjunction; expressing two elements to be taken together or in addition"
  body " to each other.\n## Used simply to connect two noun phrases, adjectives or adverbs. {{defdate|from 8th c.}}\n##* '''c. 1430''' (reprinted '''1888'''), Thomas Austin, ed., ''Two Fifteenth-century Cooke"
  body "ry-books. Harleian ms. 279 (ab. 1430), & Harl. ms. 4016 (ab. 1450), with Extracts from Ashmole ms. 1429, Laud ms. 553, & Douce ms. 55'' [Early English Text Society, Original Series; 91], London: [[w:R"
  body "outledge|N. Trübner & Co.]] for the {{w|Early English Text Society}}, volume I, <small>[[w:Online Computer Library Center|OCLC]] [http://worldcat.org/oclc/374760 374760]</small>, page 11:\n##*: Soupes"
  body " dorye. — Take gode almaunde mylke {{...}} caste þher-to Safroun '''an''' Salt {{...}}\n##* {{RQ:Shakespeare Merchant of Venice|V|1|text=Sweet lady, you have given me life '''and''' living; {{...}}}}\"
  body "n##* {{RQ:King James Version|Genesis|1|1|passage=In the beginning God created the heaven '''and''' the earth.}}\n##* {{RQ:Austen Persuasion|text=as for Mrs. Smith, she had claims of various kinds to r"
  body "ecommend her quickly '''and''' permanently.}}\n##* {{quote-journal|en|date=5 November 2011|author=Mark Townsend|journal=The Guardian\n|passage=‘The UKBA has some serious explaining to do if it is rout"
  body "inely carrying out such abusive '''and''' unlawful inspections.’}}\n## Simply connecting two clauses or sentences. {{defdate|from 8th c.}}\n##* {{quote-text|en|year=1991|author=w:Jung Chang|title=Wild"
  body " Swans\n|passage=When she saw several boys carrying a huge wooden case full of porcelain, she mumbled to Jinming that she was going to have a look, '''and''' left the room.}}\n##* {{quote-journal|en|d"
  body "ate=5 November 2011|author=Helena Smith; Tom Kington|journal=The Guardian\n|passage=\""Consensus is essential for the country,\"" he said, adding that he was not \""tied\"" to his post '''and''' was willi"
  body "ng to step aside.}}\n## Introducing a clause or sentence which follows on in time or consequence from the first. {{defdate|from 9th c.}}\n##: ''I'd been walking since sunrise, '''and''' I was hungry.'"
  body "'\n##* {{quote-text|en|year=1996|author=David Beasley|title=Chocolate for the Poor\n|passage=‘But if you think you can get it, Christian, you're a fool. Set one foot upcountry '''and''' I'll kill you."
  body "’}}\n##* {{quote-journal|en|date=22 August 2004|author=Will Buckley|journal=The Observer\n|passage=One more error '''and''' all the good work she had done on Friday would be for nought.}}\n##* '''2007"
  body "''': [[w:Jimmy Carr|Jimmy Carr]], ''[[w:8 out of 10 Cats|8 out of 10 Cats]]'', 13th day of July episode\n##*: Romance ''is'' dead; men killed it, '''and''' made women clean up the mess.\n## {{lb|en|ob"
  body "solete}} [[yet|Yet]]; [[but]]. {{defdate|10th|17th c.}}\n##* {{RQ:KJV|Matthew|XXII|text=Hee said, I goe sir, '''and''' went not.}}\n## Used to connect certain numbers: connecting units when they prece"
  body "de tens {{qualifier|now dated}}; connecting shillings to pence in a monetary quantity {{qualifier|now historical}}; connecting tens and units to hundreds, thousands etc. (now often omitted in US); to "
  body "connect fractions to wholes. {{defdate|from 10th c.}}\n##* {{RQ:Lincoln Gettysburg|Bliss|1|passage=Four score '''and''' seven years ago our fathers brought forth, on this continent, a new nation, conc"
  body "eived in Liberty, and dedicated to the proposition that all men are created equal.}}\n##* {{RQ:Sinclair Jungle|chapter=26|passage=In Chicago these latter were receiving, for the most part, eighteen ''"
  body "'and''' a half cents an hour, and the unions wished to make this the general wage for the next year.}}\n##* {{quote-book|en|year=1915|author={{w|W. Somerset Maugham}}|title=Of Human Bondage|chapter=13"
  body "\n|passage=[H]e had bought the pen-holder during his last holidays at Blackstable for one '''and''' two-pence.}}\n##* '''1956''', {{w|Dodie Smith}}, (title):\n##*: The One Hundred '''and''' One Dalmat"
  body "ians.\n## {{lb|en|now|colloquial|or|literary}} Used to connect more than two elements together in a chain, sometimes to stress the number of elements.\n##* {{RQ:Shakespeare Julius Caesar|II|2|text=And"
  body " these does she apply, for warnings '''and''' portents, / '''And''' euils imminent; and on her knee / Hath begg'd, that I will stay at home to day.}}\n##* '''1939''', Langley, Ryerson & Woolf, ''The W"
  body "izard of Oz'' (screenplay):\n##*: Lions, '''and''' tigers, '''and''' bears! Oh, my!\n## Connecting two identical elements, with implications of continued or infinite repetition. {{defdate|from 10th c."
  body "}}\n##* {{RQ:KJV|Psalms|CXLV|text=I will extol thee, my God, O king; and I will bless thy name for ever '''and''' ever.}}\n##* {{quote-journal|en|date=18 March 2011|author=Jonathan Watts|journal=The G"
  body "uardian\n|passage=He was at work in a nearby city when the tsunami struck. ‘As soon as I saw it, I called home. It rang '''and''' rang, but there was no answer.’}}\n## Introducing a [[parenthetical]] "
  body "or explanatory clause. {{defdate|from 10th c.}}\n##* {{quote-text|en|year=1918|author=w:George W. E. Russell|title=Prime Ministers and Some Others\n|passage=The word \""capable\"" occurs in Mr. Fisher's"
  body " Bill, '''and''' rightly, because our mental and physical capacities are infinitely varied.}}\n##* {{quote-journal|en|journal=The Guardian|date=29 Jan 2008\n|passage=President Pervez Musharraf is undo"
  body "ubtedly sincere in his belief that he, '''and''' he alone, can save Pakistan from the twin perils of terrorism and anarchy.}}\n## Introducing the continuation of narration from a previous understood p"
  body "oint; also used alone as a question: ‘and so what?’.\n##* {{RQ:KJV|Revelation|XIV|text='''And''' I heard a voice from heaven, as the voice of many waters, and as the voice of a great thunder: and I he"
  body "ard the voice of harpers harping with their harps{{nb...}}.}}\n##* {{RQ:Dickens Great Expectations|text=‘You take it smoothly now,’ said I, ‘but you were very serious last night, when you swore it was"
  body " Death.’ ‘'''And''' so I swear it is Death,’ said he, putting his pipe back in his mouth{{nb...}}.}}\n##* {{quote-text|en|year=1914|author=w:Saki; ‘The Lull’|title=Beasts and Superbeasts\n|passage=‘''"
  body "'And''', Vera,’ added Mrs. Durmot, turning to her sixteen-year-old niece, ‘be careful what colour ribbon you wear in your hair{{nb...}}.’}}\n## {{lb|en|now|dialectal|_|or somewhat|_|colloquial}} Used "
  body "to connect two verbs where the second is dependent on the first: ‘[[to]]’. Used especially after {{m|en|come}}, {{m|en|go}} and {{m|en|try}}. {{defdate|from 14th c.}}\n##* {{RQ:Austen Sanditon|text=Be"
  body "yond paying her a few charming compliments and amusing her with gay conversation, had he done anything at all to try '''and''' gain her affection?}}\n##* {{RQ:Thackeray Vanity Fair|passage=\""What have"
  body " you a been '''and''' given Pitt's wife?\"" said the individual in ribbons, when Pitt and Lady Jane had taken leave of the old gentleman.}}\n##* {{quote-text|en|year=1989|author=w:James Kelman|title=A "
  body "Disaffection\n|passage=Remember '''and''' help yourself to the soup! called Gavin.}}\n## Introducing a [[qualitative]] difference between things having the same name; \""as well as other\"". {{defdate|f"
  body "rom 16th c.}}\n##* {{quote-text|en|year=1936|title=The Labour Monthly|volume=XVIII\n|passage=Undoubtedly every party makes mistakes. But there are mistakes '''and''' mistakes.}}\n##* {{quote-text|en|y"
  body "ear=1972|title=Esquire|volume=LXXVIII\n|passage=\""There are managers '''and''' there are managers,\"" he tells me. \""I'm totally involved in every aspect of Nina's career.\""}}\n## Used to combine numbe"
  body "rs in [[addition]]; [[plus]] (with singular or plural verb). {{defdate|from 17th c.}}\n##: ''Two '''and''' two is/are four''.\n##* {{quote-text|en|year=1791|author=w:James Boswell|title=Life of Samuel"
  body " Johnson\n|passage=‘Nobody attempts to dispute that two '''and''' two make four: but with contests concerning moral truth, human passions are generally mixed{{nb...}}.’}}\n##* {{quote-text|en|year=187"
  body "1|author=w:Lewis Carroll|title=Through the Looking-Glass, and What Alice Found There\n|passage=‘Can you do Addition?’ the White Queen asked. ‘What's one '''and''' one '''and''' one '''and''' one '''an"
  body "d''' one '''and''' one '''and''' one '''and''' one '''and''' one '''and''' one?’}}\n# {{lb|en|heading}} ''Expressing a condition.''\n## {{lb|en|now|US|_|dialect}} [[if|If]]; provided that. {{defdate|f"
  body "rom 13th c.}}\n##* {{quote-text|en|year=1485|author=Sir Thomas Malory|title=Le Morte Darthur|section=Book VII\n|passage=\""Where ys Sir Launcelot?\"" seyde King Arthure. \""'''And''' he were here, he wol"
  body "de nat grucche to do batayle for you.\""}}\n##* {{RQ:Tyndale NT|Matthew|XIV|text=Peter answered, and sayde: master, '''and''' thou be he, bidde me come unto the on the water.}}\n##* {{quote-text|en|yea"
  body "r=1958|author=w:Shirley Ann Grau|title=The Hard Blue Sky\n|passage=\""'''And''' he went slower,\"" Mike said softly, \""he go better.\""}}\n## {{lb|en|obsolete}} [[as if|As if]], [[as though]]. {{defdate|"
  body "15th|17th c.}}\n##* {{RQ:Shakespeare Midsummer|I|2|text=I will roare you, '''and''' 'twere any Nightingale.}}\n##* {{RQ:Bacon Essayes|chapter=Of Innovations|passage=As they will set an house on fire, "
  body "'''and''' it were but to roast their eggs.}}\n# {{lb|en|mathematics|logic}} Connecting two [[well-formed formula|well-formed formulas]] to create a new well-formed formula that requires it to only be "
  body "true when both of the two formulas are true.\n\n=====Usage notes=====\n{{col-top|2|Usage notes}}\nBeginning a sentence with {{m|en|and}} or other coordinating conjunctions is considered incorrect by c"
  body "lassical grammarians arguing that a coordinating conjunction at the start of a sentence has nothing to connect, but use of the word in this way is very common. The practice will be found in literature"
  body " from Anglo-Saxon times onwards, especially as an aid to continuity in narrative and dialogue. The ''OED'' provides examples from the 9th century to the 19th century, including one from Shakespeare’s "
  body "''King John:'' “''Arthur''. Must you with hot Irons, burne out both mine eyes? ''Hubert.'' Young boy, I must. ''Arthur''. And will you? ''Hubert''. And I will.” It is also used for other rhetorical pu"
  body "rposes, especially to denote surprise\n\n<blockquote>(O John! and you have seen him! And are you really going?—1884 in ''OED'') </blockquote>\n\nand sometimes just to introduce an improvised afterthou"
  body "ght\n\n<blockquote>(I’m going to swim. And don’t you dare watch—G. Butler, 1983)</blockquote>\n\nIt is, however, poor style to separate short statements into separate sentences when no special effect "
  body "is needed: ''I opened the door and I looked into the room'' (not *''I opened the door. And I looked into the room''). Combining sentences or starting with ''in addition'' or ''moreover'' is preferred "
  body "in formal writing.\n\n{{m|en|and|And}} is often omitted for contextual effects of various kinds, especially between sequences of descriptive adjectives which can be separated by commas or simply by sp"
  body "aces\n\n<blockquote>(The teeming jerrybuilt dun-coloured traffic-ridden deafening city—Penelope Lively, 1987)</blockquote>\n\nIn U.S. financial contexts such as [[cheque|check]] writing, '''and''' is "
  body "often proscribed within full dollar amounts, reserved for use only immediately before the cent value. For instance, $150 is written \""one hundred fifty\"", whereas \""one hundred '''and''' fifty\"" is ar"
  body "guably ambiguous and could be taken to mean $100.50 instead. Some even teach that '''and''' literally means a decimal point, although a standard writing would at least denote the fractional dollar val"
  body "ue as hundredths, e.g. with \""/xx\"".\n{{col-bottom}}\n\n=====Synonyms=====\n* {{sense|used to connect two similar words or phrases}} {{l|en|as well as}}, {{l|en|together with}}, {{l|en|in addition to}"
  body "}\n* {{sense|informal}} {{l|en|&}}, {{l|en|'n'}}, {{l|en|+}}\n* {{sense|in artist collaborations}} {{l|en|x}}\n\n=====Derived terms=====\n{{col|en\n|Antigua and Barbuda\n|Bosnia and Herzegovina\n|Fren"
  body "ch Southern and Antarctic Lands\n|fish and chips\n|piece and crisps\n|rock and roll\n|and all\n|and of course\n|and then everyone clapped\n|AND gate\n|Rhode Island and Providence Plantations\n|Saint K"
  body "itts and Nevis\n|Saint Pierre and Miquelon\n|Saint Vincent and the Grenadines\n|São Tomé and Príncipe\n|South Georgia and the South Sandwich Islands\n|Turks and Caicos Islands\n|Trinidad and Tobago\n|"
  body "Wallis and Futuna}}\n\n=====Translations=====\n{{see translation subpage|Conjunction}}\n\n=====See also=====\n{{col|en\n|false\n|if\n|iff\n|implies\n|nand\n|nor\n|not\n|or\n|true\n|xor\n}}\n\n=====See"
  body " also=====\n* {{l|en|formal logic}}\n\n====Noun====\n{{en-noun}}\n\n# {{senseid|en|second half of divided beat}}{{lb|en|music|often informal}} In [[rhythm]], the second half of a divided [[beat]].\n#:"
  body " {{cot|en|e<id:music>|a<id:music>}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=2006|author=Gordon Goodwin|title=Gordon Goodwin's Big Phat Band: Trumpet|page=51\n|passage=The same goes for measure 42, when you begin the"
  body " phrase on the '''and''' of 1, because that kind of lick can easily bog down the time.}}\n\n===Etymology 2===\n{{rfv|en}}\n{{inh+|en|enm|ande}}, from {{inh|en|ang|anda||grudge, enmity, malice, envy, h"
  body "atred, anger, zeal, annoyance, vexation; zeal; injury, mischief; fear, horror}} and {{der|en|non|andi||breath, wind, spirit}}; both from {{der|en|gem-pro|*anadô||breath, anger, zeal}}, from {{der|en|i"
  body "ne-pro|*h₂enh₁-||to breathe, blow}}.\n\nCognate with {{cog|de|[[Ahnd]], [[And]]||woe, grief}}, {{cog|da|ånde||breath}}, {{cog|sv|[[anda]], [[ande]]||spirit, breath, wind, ingenuity, intellect}}, {{cog"
  body "|is|andi||spirit}}, {{cog|sq|ëndë||pleasure, delight}}, {{cog|la|animus||spirit, soul}}. Related to {{m|en|onde}}.\n\n====Alternative forms====\n* {{alter|en|aynd|eynd}}\n\n====Noun====\n{{en-noun}}\n"
  body "\n# {{lb|en|UK|_|dialectal}} [[breath|Breath]].\n# {{lb|en|UK|_|dialectal}} {{w|Sea smoke}}; [[steam fog]].\n\n===Etymology 3===\n{{rfv|en}}\n{{inh+|en|enm|anden}}, from {{inh|en|ang|andian||to be env"
  body "ious or jealous, envy}} and {{der|en|non|anda||to breathe}}; both from {{der|en|gem-pro|*anadōną||to breathe, sputter}}. Cognate with {{cog|de|ahnden||to avenge, punish}}, {{cog|da|ånde||to breathe}},"
  body " {{cog|sv|andas||to breathe}}, {{cog|is|anda||to breathe}}. See above.\n\n====Alternative forms====\n* {{l|en|eind}}, {{l|en|eynd}}, {{l|en|ein}}\n\n====Verb====\n{{en-verb}}\n\n# {{lb|en|UK|_|dialect"
  body "al|intransitive}} To [[breathe]]; [[whisper]]; [[devise]]; [[imagine]].\n\n===Anagrams===\n* {{anagrams|en|a=adn|-dan|ADN|DAN|DNA|Dan|Dan.|NAD|NDA|dan|dna|nad}}\n\n{{cln|en|coordinating conjunctions|3"
  body "-letter words}}\n\n==Azerbaijani==\n{{az-variant|анд|آند}}\n\n===Etymology===\nFrom {{inh|az|trk-pro|*ānt|t=oath}}.<ref>{{R:trk-pro:SDM|*Ānt|293}}</ref> Cognate with {{cog|otk|𐰦}}, {{cog|tr|ant}}.\n\n"
  body "===Pronunciation===\n* {{IPA|az|[ɑnd]}}\n* {{audio|az|LL-Q9292 (aze)-Zardabi Bakuvi-and.wav|a=Baku}}\n\n===Noun===\n{{az-noun}}\n\n# [[oath]]\n#: {{syn|az|əhd}}\n\n====Declension====\n{{az-decl-noun|a"
  body "|c}}\n\n====Derived terms====\n* {{l|az|and içmək||to take an oath}}\n\n===References===\n<references/>\n\n==Danish==\n\n===Etymology===\n{{inh+|da|non|ǫnd}}, from {{inh|da|gem-pro|*anadz}}, cognate w"
  body "ith {{cog|de|Ente}}, {{cog|nl|eend}}. The Germanic noun derives from {{inh|da|ine-pro|*h₂énh₂ts||duck}}, which is also the source of {{cog|la|anas}}, {{cog|grc|νῆττα}}, {{cog|lt|ántis}}, {{cog|sa|आति|"
  body "tr=ātí}}.\n\nThe sense of \""false story\"" is a {{semantic loan|da|fr|canard|nocap=1}}.\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{IPA|da|/anˀ/|[ænˀ]}}\n* {{rhymes|da|and|s=1}}\n\n===Noun===\n{{da-noun|en|ænder}}\n\n"
  body "# [[duck]] {{gloss|{{taxfmt|Anatinae|family}}}}\n# [[canard]] {{q|false or misleading report or story}}\n\n====Declension====\n{{da-decl|en|ænder|ænderne}}\n\n====Related terms====\n* {{l|da|anderik}}"
  body "\n\n===Further reading===\n* {{R:DDO}}\n\n{{C|da|Ducks}}\n\n==Estonian==\n\n===Etymology===\nFrom {{inh|et|urj-fin-pro|*anti}}, from the root of {{m|et|andma}}. Cognate with {{cog|fi|anti}}.\n\n===Pro"
  body "nunciation===\n* {{et-IPA|an'd}}\n\n===Noun===\n{{et-noun|anni|andi}}\n\n# [[offering]], [[gift]]\n# [[alms]], [[donation]]\n# [[giftedness]], [[talent]]\n# act of [[giving]]\n\n====Declension====\n{{"
  body "et-decl2|anni|andi|andide|ande||andi|||andisid|type=paks}}\n\n==Fingallian==\n\n===Conjunction===\n{{head|gmw-fin|conjunction}}\n\n# {{l|en|and}}\n\n==Gothic==\n\n===Romanization===\n{{got-rom}}\n\n# "
  body "{{romanization of|got|𐌰𐌽𐌳}}\n\n==Livonian==\n\n===Etymology 1===\n{{etymid|liv|gift}}\nFrom {{inh|liv|urj-fin-pro|*anti}}.\n\n====Pronunciation====\n{{liv-p}}\n\n====Noun====\n{{head|liv|noun}}\n\n# ["
  body "[gift]], [[present]]\n# [[talent]], [[gift]]\n\n=====Declension=====\n{{liv-decl|94}}\n\n====References====\n* {{R:liv:LEL|and}}\n\n===Etymology 2===\n{{etymid|liv|S-give}}\n\n====Verb====\n{{head|liv"
  body "|verb}}\n\n# {{liv-Salaca form of|andõ|t=to give}}\n\n====References====\n* {{R:liv:LDW}}\n* {{R:liv:SLW}}\n\n==Middle English==\n\n===Etymology 1===\n{{etymon|enm|id=conjunction|:inh|ang:and}}\nFrom "
  body "{{inh|enm|ang|and}}, {{m|ang|ond}}, {{m|ang|end}}, from {{inh|enm|gmw-pro|*andi}}, from {{inh|enm|gem-pro|*andi}}, from {{inh|enm|ine-pro|*h₂énti}}.\n\n====Alternative forms====\n* {{alter|enm|annd|an"
  body "t|an|en}}\n* {{alter|enm|⁊|&}}\n\n====Pronunciation====\n* {{IPA|enm|/and/}}\n* {{IPA|enm|/an/|/ɛn/|a=unstressed}}\n\n====Conjunction====\n{{head|enm|conjunction}}\n\n# {{l|en|and}}, {{l|en|and}} [[th"
  body "en]] {{gloss|connects two elements of a sentence}}\n#* {{RQ:Ormulum|d|3|url=https://digital.bodleian.ox.ac.uk/objects/90a06f70-880a-4b5b-bd30-798710afff11/surfaces/a2980d0a-ac52-4383-ba1b-bc0a6a6f567a"
  body "/|Nu broþerr Ƿallꞇ͛. broþerͬ min. Affꞇ͛ þe flæsheſſ kĩde⹎ '''⁊''' broþerͬ mın ı crıſſtenndom. Þurrh fulluhht⹎<!--?--> '''⁊''' þurrh troꟕþe⹎ '''⁊''' broþerr mın ı ꟑodeſſ huſ {{...}}|Now, Brother Walter"
  body ", my brother by blood relation '''and''' in Christendom, through baptism '''and''' faith, '''and''' my brother in God's house {{...}}}}\n#* {{quote-book|enm|year=c. 1340|title=w:Ayenbite of Inwyt|auth"
  body "or=Dan Michel|chapter=Þe oþer Godes Heste|passage=Ac þe ilke / þet zuereþ hidousliche be god / oþer by his halȝen / '''and''' him to-breȝþ / '''and''' zayþ him sclondres / þet ne byeþ naȝt to zigge: þ"
  body "e ilke zeneȝeþ dyadliche {{...}}|translation=But one who / hideously swears by God / or by his emissaries / '''and''' who tears him apart / '''while''' saying to him lies / that shouldn't be said: the"
  body "y sin grievously. {{...}} }}\n#* {{quote-book|enm|year=c. 1380|title=Sir Firumbras|lines=4413–4414|passage=\""Lordes\"", quaþ Richard, \""Buþ noȝt agast, Ac holdeþ forþ ȝour way / '''an''' hast & boldeli"
  body "che doþ ȝour dede {{...}}\"" |translation=\""Lords\"", said Richard, \""Don't be frightened, but hold your way forwards / '''and''' quickly and boldy do your deed {{...}}\"" }}\n#* {{RQ:Wycliffe NT Lichfie"
  body "ld|book=Revelation|chapter=1|verse=8|leaf=117|side=v|passage=ȝhe amen / I am alpha '''⁊''' oo þe bigynnyng '''⁊''' þe ende ſeiþ þe loꝛd god þat is / '''⁊''' þat was. '''⁊''' that is to comynge almyȝti"
  body "|translation=You, Amen! I am Alpha '''and''' O, the beginning '''and''' the end, says the Lord God; that is, that was, '''and''' that which will come, almighty.}}\n#* {{RQ:Chaucer Canterbury Tales|ver"
  body "sion=Hg|title=Prologue|folio=2|url=https://viewer.library.wales/4628556#?c=&m=&s=&cv=14|passage=Whan that Auerill w{{sup|t}} his shoures soote / The droghte of march hath &#42833;ced to the roote / ''"
  body "'And''' bathed euery veyne in swich lycour / Of which v̄tu engendred is the flour{{...}}|translation=When that April, with its sweet showers / Has pierced March's drought to the root / '''And''' bathe"
  body "d every vein in fluid such that / with its power, the flower is made{{...}}}}\n# [[however]], [[yet]], [[but]], [[though]]. [[while]]\n# [[if]], supposing that, [[whether]].\n# {{lb|enm|rare}} [[as|As"
  body "]] [[though]], like, in a manner suggesting.\n\n=====Descendants=====\n* {{desc|en|and}}\n* {{desc|sco|an}}\n* {{desc|yol|an|alts=1}}\n\n=====References=====\n* {{R:MED Online|entry=and|pos=conj. (& a"
  body "dv.)|id=MED1536|accessdate=2019-01-14}}\n\n===Etymology 2===\n\n====Noun====\n{{head|enm|noun|altform=1}}\n\n# {{tlb|enm|Northern ME}} {{alt form|enm|onde|id=breath|t=breath}}\n\n==Norwegian Bokmål==\"
  body "n{{wp|no:ender}}\n\n===Etymology===\n{{inh+|nb|non|ǫnd}}, from {{inh|nb|gem-pro|*anadz}}, from {{inh|nb|ine-pro|*h₂énh₂ts||duck}}.\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{IPA|nb|/ɑnː/|/ɑnd/}}\n* {{audio|nb|no-and"
  body ".ogg}}\n\n===Noun===\n{{nb-noun-c||end}}\n\n# a [[duck]]\n# [[canard]] (false or misleading report or story)\n\n====Derived terms====\n* {{l|nb|Andeby||[[Duckburg]]}}\n* {{l|nb|andunge}}\n\n===Referen"
  body "ces===\n* {{R:nb:OB}}\n\n{{C|nb|Birds}}\n\n==Norwegian Nynorsk==\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{IPA|nn|/an(d)/|[ɐ̞nd]|[ɐ̞nː]}} {{nn-pronu-note}}\n\n===Etymology 1===\n{{wp|nn:}}\nFrom {{inh|nn|non|ǫnd}},"
  body " from {{inh|nn|gem-pro|*anadz}}, from {{inh|nn|ine-pro|*h₂énh₂ts||duck}}.\n\n====Alternative forms====\n* {{alt|nn|ond}}\n* {{alt|nn|ønd||dialectal}}\n\n====Noun====\n{{nn-noun-f1||end}}\n\n# a [[duck"
  body "]] {{q|waterbird}}\n\n=====Declension=====\n{{nn-decl-f-c|and|end}}\n{{nn-decl-f-c-aasen|and|end|ond}}\n\n=====Derived terms=====\n{{col4|nn\n|andebryst\n|Andeby\n|andebøle\n|andedam\n|andedun\n|andef"
  body "amilie\n|andefugl\n|andeegg\n|andekall\n|andestegg\n|andunge\n|avisand\n|dykkand\n|fiskand\n|grasand\n|gravand\n|isand\n|krikkand\n|kvinand\n|laksand\n|stokkand\n|svartand\n|taffeland\n|toppand\n|vill"
  body "and\n}}\n\n===Etymology 2===\n{{root|nn|ine-pro|*h₂enh₁-}}\nFrom {{inh|nn|non|ǫnd}}.\n\n====Alternative forms====\n* {{alt|nn|ond}}\n\n====Noun====\n{{nn-noun-f1}}\n\n# {{senseid|nn|breath}} [[breath]"
  body "], [[spirit]]\n#: {{syn|nn|ande|pust}}\n\n===Etymology 3===\n\n====Verb====\n{{head|nn|verb form}}\n\n# {{infl of|nn|ande||imp}}\n\n===References===\n* {{R:nn:OB}}\n\n===Anagrams===\n* {{anagrams|nn|a"
  body "=adn|and-|dan}}\n\n{{C|nn|Birds}}\n\n==Old English==\n\n===Alternative forms===\n* {{alter|ang|ond|end}}\n* {{alt|ang|ᚪᚾᛞ|ᛖᚾᛞ||{{w|Franks Casket}}}}\n\n===Etymology===\n{{etymon|ang|:inh|gem-pro:*andi"
  body "}}\nFrom {{inh|ang|gem-pro|[[*anda]], [[*andi]]}}, probably from {{der|ang|ine-pro|*h₂énti||facing opposite, near, in front of, before}}. Compare {{cog|ofs|and}}, {{cog|osx|endi}}, {{cog|goh|unti}}, {"
  body "{cog|non|enn}}.\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{ang-IPA|and|}}\n* {{rhymes|ang|ɑnd|s=1}}\n\n===Conjunction===\n{{head|ang|conjunction}}\n\n# {{l|en|and}}\n#* {{quote-book|ang|text=''Þonne iċ mec onhebbe '"
  body "''ond''' hī onhnīgaþ tō mē, moniġe mid miltse, þǣr iċ monnum sceal īċan upcyme ēadiġnesse.''|t=When I raise myself up '''and''' they bow down to me, many with mercy, then I shall increase rising of ha"
  body "ppiness for men.|title=Exeter Book Riddle 30|year=10th century|url=https://www.oldenglishaerobics.net/riddles.html#w0000250}}\n\n====Synonyms====\n* {{l|ang|⁊}} {{qualifier|symbol}}\n\n====Descendants"
  body "====\n* {{desctree|enm|and}}\n\n===Adverb===\n{{ang-adv}}\n\n# [[even]]; [[also]]\n\n==Old Frisian==\n\n===Alternative forms===\n* {{alt|ofs|ande|ende}}\n\n===Etymology===\n{{inh+|ofs|gem-pro|*andi}},"
  body " from {{inh|ofs|ine-pro|*h₂énti||facing opposite, near, in front of, before}}. Compare {{cog|ang|and}}, {{cog|osx|endi}}, {{cog|goh|unti}}, {{cog|non|enn}}.\n\n===Conjunction===\n{{head|ofs|conjunctio"
  body "n}}\n\n# [[and#English|and]]\n\n====Descendants====\n* {{desc|frr|än}}\n* {{desc|stq|un}}\n* {{desc|fy|en|in}}\n\n==Old Irish==\n\n===Etymology===\nFrom {{inh|sga|cel-pro|*andom}}, from {{der|sga|ine-"
  body "pro|*h₁n̥dó}}. The adverbial sense of this term is the original one, and it has an etymology independent of {{m|sga|hi|i}}.\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{sga-IPA}}\n\n===Pronoun===\n{{head|sga|prepositi"
  body "onal pronoun}}\n\n# {{infl of|sga|hi||3|s|m//n|dat}}: [[in]] [[him]], [[in]] [[it]]\n#* {{RQ:sga-gloss|Ml|31|b|23}}\n#*: {{quote|sga|in bélrai .i. is '''and''' atá gním tengad isind huiliu labramar-ni"
  body "|of speech, i.e. the action of the tongue is in it, in all that we say}}\n\n===Adverb===\n{{head|sga|adverb}}\n\n# [[there]]\n#* {{RQ:sga:Glosses|Tur|110c}}\n#*: {{quote|sga|Ba bés leusom do·bertis dá"
  body " boc leu dochum tempuil, ⁊ no·léicthe indala n‑ái fon díthrub co pecad in popuil, ⁊ do·bertis maldachta foir, ⁊ n⟨o⟩·oircthe didiu '''and''' ó popul tar cenn a pecthae ind aile.\n|It was a custom with"
  body " them that two he-goats were brought by them to the temple, and one of the two of them was let go to the wilderness with the sin of the people, and curses were put upon him, and thereupon the other wa"
  body "s slain '''there''' by the people for their sins.}}\n# [[then]], [[in that case]]\n#* {{RQ:sga:Glosses|Wb|4|a|27}}\n#*: {{quote|sga|Is '''and''' didiu for·téit {{m|la||spiritus}} ar n-énirti-ni in tai"
  body "n bes n-inun accobor lenn .i. la corp {{m|la||et}} anim {{m|la||et}} la spirut.\n|So it is '''then''' that the spirit helps our weakness when we have the same desire, to wit, body and soul and spirit."
  body "}}\n\n====Descendants====\n* {{desc|mga|ann}}\n** {{desc|ga|ann}}\n** {{desc|gv|ayn}}\n** {{desc|gd|ann}}\n\n==Polish==\n\n===Alternative forms===\n* {{alt|pl|ampt||Eastern Greater Poland|Kłodawa}}\n\"
  body "n===Etymology===\n{{ety|pl|:bor|de:Amt|text=+|tree=1}}\n\n===Pronunciation===\n{{pl-pr|-|EGP=#}}\n\n===Noun===\n{{pl-noun|m-in}}\n\n# {{lb|pl|Eastern Greater Poland|Kłodawa|historic}} [[starost]]'s [["
  body "manor house]]\n#: {{uxa|pl|Byłem na '''andzie'''.|I was at the '''starost's manor house'''.}}\n\n===Further reading===\n* {{R:pl:Łopaciński:1893||692|5}}\n\n{{C|pl|Buildings|Housing}}\n\n==Scots==\n\n"
  body "===Conjunction===\n{{h|sco|conj}}\n\n# {{alternative form of|sco|an}}\n\n====Usage notes====\n* While ''and'' is relatively often written due to English influence, it is seldom pronounced as such, mak"
  body "ing way for {{m|sco|an}}. <ref> https://dsl.ac.uk/entry/snd/and_conj1 </ref>\n\n====References====\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Swedish==\n{{wp|sv:}}\n[[File:Mallard_drake_swimming.jpg|thumb|300px|en '''and''' ("
  body "{{l|sv|gräsand|gräs'''and'''}}) [a '''(wild) duck''' (mallard)] ]]\n\n===Etymology===\n{{inh+|sv|non|ǫnd}}, from {{inh|sv|gem-pro|*anadz}}, from {{inh|sv|ine-pro|*h₂énh₂ts|t=duck}}.\n\n===Pronunciatio"
  body "n===\n* {{IPA|sv|/and/}}\n* {{audio|sv|Sv-and.ogg}}\n\n===Noun===\n{{sv-noun|c}}\n\n# a wild [[duck]]\n#: {{ux|sv|mata '''änderna''' i parken|feed '''the ducks''' in the park}}\n## {{lb|sv|especially}"
  body "} a [[mallard]]\n##: {{syn|sv|gräsand}}\n\n====Declension====\n{{sv-infl-noun-c-r|2=ande|3=ände}}\n\n====Related terms====\n{{col3\n|sv|andfågel\n|andjakt\n|andmat\n|andrake\n|andsträck\n|andunge\n|gr"
  body "äsand\n}}\n\n====See also====\n* {{l|sv|anka}} {{q|domesticated duck}}\n\n===References===\n* {{R:svenska.se|so}}\n* {{R:svenska.se|saol}}\n* {{R:svenska.se|saob}}\n\n===Anagrams===\n* {{anagrams|sv|a"
  body "=adn|-nad|Dan|dan}}\n\n{{cln|sv|nouns with irregular plurals}}\n{{C|sv|Ducks}}\n\n==Turkish==\n\n===Noun===\n{{head|tr|noun}}\n\n# {{archaic form of|tr|ant|t=oath}}\n\n==Yola==\n\n===Conjunction===\n{"
  body "{head|yol|conjunction}}\n\n# {{alternative form of|yol|an||and}}\n#* {{quote-book|yol|year=1867|title=GLOSSARY OF THE DIALECT OF FORTH AND BARGY|passage=Jaude '''and''' maude.|translation=Crowds '''an"
  body "d''' throngs.}}\n#* {{quote-book|yol|year=1867|chapter=THE WEDDEEN O BALLYMORE|page=93|title=SONGS, ETC. IN THE DIALECT OF FORTH AND BARGY|passage=\""steoute '''and''' straung,\""|translation=stout '''a"
  body "nd''' strong;}}\n\n===References===\n* {{R:Poole 1867|page=49}}\n\n==Zealandic==\n\n===Etymology===\n{{dercat|zea|gem-pro|inh=1}}\n{{inh+|zea|dum|hant}}, from {{inh|zea|odt|hant}}, from {{inh|zea|gmw-"
  body "pro|*handu}}.\n\n===Noun===\n{{zea-noun|f}}\n\n# {{topics|zea|Body parts}} [[#English|hand]]\n\n====Alternative forms====\n* {{l|zea|'and}}""}}"

response_0006_api_php_action_parse_pag
  url "https://en.wiktionary.org/w/api.php?action=parse&page=apple&prop=wikitext&formatversion=2&format=json&redirects=1"
  body "{""parse"":{""title"":""apple"",""pageid"":2154,""redirects"":[],""wikitext"":""{{also|Apple|äpple}}\n==English==\n{{was wotd|2024|October|21}}\n\n===Etymology===\n{{etymon|en|id=fruit|:inh|enm:appel<id:apple>|tre"
  body "e=1}}\n{{multiple images\n| direction = vertical\n| image1   = Red Apple.jpg\n| caption1 = An apple ({{senseno|en|Q89}}).\n| image2   = Apple Blossom Time at Oak Glen, CA 3-16 (26094251756).jpg\n| cap"
  body "tion2 = An apple ({{senseno|en|apple tree}}) or [[apple tree]] in [[blossom#Noun|blossom]].\n| image3   = Frans Floris - The Fall of Man - Google Art Project.jpg\n| caption3 = ''{{w|The Fall of Man}}'"
  body "' ({{circa2|1560|short=1}}) by {{w|Frans Floris}},{{ref|group=n|name=n1|From the collection of the {{w|Malmö Art Museum}} in [[Malmö]], [[Scania]], [[Sweden]].}} which depicts [[Adam and Eve]] in the "
  body "[[Garden of Eden]] with apples ({{senseno|en|forbidden fruit}}) or [[forbidden fruit]].\n}}\n\nThe {{glossary|noun}} is derived from {{inh|en|enm|appel|t=''Malus domestica'' fruit or tree, apple; any "
  body "type of fruit, nut, or tuber; tree bearing fruit; (''figurative'') ball, sphere; (''Christianity'') forbidden fruit in Eden}},<ref>{{R:MED Online|entry=appel|pos=n|id=MED1901}}</ref> from {{inh|en|ang"
  body "|æppel|t=apple; any type of fruit; (''figurative'') ball, sphere; eyeball}}, from {{inh|en|gmw-pro|*applu|t=apple; any type of fruit}}, from {{inh|en|gem-pro|*aplaz|t=apple; any type of fruit}}, from "
  body "{{inh|en|ine-pro|*h₂ébōl}}, {{m|ine-pro|*h₂ébl̥|t=apple}}.<ref name=\""OED\"">{{R:OED Online|pos=n|id=1190710016|date=September 2024|nodot=1}}; {{R:Lexico|pos=n}}</ref>\n\nAs regards {{senseno|en|forbid"
  body "den fruit|t=forbidden fruit}}, the type of fruit eaten by Adam and Eve is not identified in the {{w|Book of Genesis}} in the [[Bible]]. It may have come to be identified with the apple because of the "
  body "similarity between {{noncog|la|mālum|t=apple}} and {{m|la|malum|t=evil; misery, torment; wrongdoing}}.<ref name=\""OED\""/>\n\nThe {{glossary|verb}} is derived from the noun.<ref>{{R:OED Online|pos=v|id"
  body "=9926648781|date=June 2024}}</ref>\n{{col-top|2|cog}}\nCognate with {{cog|sco|aipple|t=apple}}, {{cog|frr|aapel}}, {{m|frr|Oapel}}, {{m|frr|ååpel|t=apple}}, {{cog|stq|Apel}}, {{m|stq|Appel|t=apple}}, "
  body "{{cog|fy|apel}}, {{m|fy|appel|t=apple}}, {{cog|gsw|effél}}, {{m|gsw|epfel}}, {{m|gsw|epfil}}, {{m|gsw|öpfil|t=apple}}, {{cog|bar|eipfele}}, {{m|bar|epfl}}, {{m|bar|Åpfe|t=apple}}, {{cog|cim|oupfal}}, "
  body "{{m|cim|öpfel}}, {{m|cim|öpfl|t=apple}}, {{cog|nl|appel|t=apple}}, {{cog|de|Apfel|t=apple}}, {{cog|nds-de|Appel|t=apple}}, {{cog|li|Ape̩l}}, {{m|li|appel|t=apple}}, {{cog|lb|Apel|t=apple}}, {{cog|mhn|"
  body "epfl|t=apple}}, {{cog|wym|epuł|t=apple}}, {{cog|yi|עפּל|t=apple}}, {{cog|da|æble|t=apple}}, {{cog|fo|epl}}, {{m|fo|epli|t=apple; potato}}, {{cog|is|epli|t=apple}}, {{cog|nb,nn|eple|t=apple}}, {{cog|sv"
  body "|äpple|t=apple}}, {{cog|gme-cgo|apel|t=apple}}, {{cog|ga|úll|t=apple}}, {{cog|lt|óbuolỹs|t=apple}}, {{cog|ru|я́блоко|t=apple}}, {{cog|cy|afal|t=apple}}, possibly {{cog|grc|ἄμπελος|t=vine}}.\n{{col-bot"
  body "tom}}\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{IPA|en|/ˈæpəl/|[ˈæpəl]|~|[ˈæpl̩]}}\n** {{audio|en|LL-Q1860 (eng)-Naomi Persephone Amethyst (NaomiAmethyst)-apple.wav|a=GA}}\n** {{audio|en|En-uk-apple.ogg|a=RP}}\n** "
  body "{{audio|en|LL-Q1860 (eng)-Vealhurl-apple.wav|a=Southern England}}\n** {{audio|en|En-us-apple.ogg|a=GA}}\n* {{IPA|en|/ˈæ.pɘl/|/ˈa.pɘl/|a=Indic}}\n:: the final L might be retroflexed; compare Malayalam "
  body "[[ആപ്പിൾ]].\n* {{rhymes|en|æpəl|s=2}}\n* {{hyph|en|ap|ple}}\n\n===Noun===\n{{en-noun}}\n\n# A [[common#Adjective|common]], [[firm#Adjective|firm]], [[round#Adjective|round]] [[fruit#Noun|fruit]] [[pro"
  body "duce#Verb|produced]] by a [[tree#Noun|tree]] of the [[genus]] {{taxfmt|Malus|genus}}.\n#: {{hypernyms|en|fruit|hand fruit|pome}}\n## {{senseid|en|Q89}} The fruit of the tree {{taxfmt|Malus domestica|s"
  body "pecies}}, chiefly with a [[green#Adjective|green]], [[red#Adjective|red]], or [[yellow#Adjective|yellow]] [[skin#Noun|skin]], [[cultivate]]d in [[temperate#Adjective|temperate]] [[climate#Noun|climate"
  body "s]] for [[cidermaking]], [[cooking#Noun|cooking]], and [[eating#Noun|eating]]. {{defdate|from 9th c.}}\n##* {{RQ:Elyot Castel of Helth|chapter=Of Apples|folio=21|passage=All '''apples''' eaten ſoone a"
  body "fter y&#877; they be gathered, are cold, hard to digeſt, and do make ill and corrupted bloud, but being wel kept vntill y&#868; next winter, or the year folowing, eatẽ {{quote-gloss|eaten}} after meal"
  body "es, they are right holeſome, & doe confyrme the ſtomacke, & make good digeſtion, ſpecially if they be roſted or baked, {{...}}}}\n##* {{RQ:Pliny Holland Historie of the World|tome=1|book=VI|chapter=Th"
  body "e Arij, and Other Nations Depending unto Them|page=128|passage=[T]hey {{quote-gloss|''i.e.'', writers}} aſſigne and lay to India, the countrey of the Aſpagores, ſo plentifull in vines, laurels, and bo"
  body "x, and generally of all ſorts of '''apple''' trees and other fruitfull trees that grovv vvithin Greece.}}\n##* {{RQ:Bunyan Pilgrim's Progress|page=233|passage=VVhat of my ''droſs'' thou findeſt there,"
  body " be bold / To throvv avvay, but yet preserve the Gold. / VVhat if my Gold be vvrapped up in Ore? / None throvvs avvay the '''Apple''' for the Core.}}\n##* {{RQ:Spectator|author=Steele|issue=509|date=1"
  body "4 October 1712|page=501|passage=Instead of the assembly of honourable merchants, substantial tradesmen, and knowing masters of ships; the mumpers, the halt, the blind, and the lame; your venders of tr"
  body "ash, '''apples''', plums; your ragamuffins, rakeshames, and wenches; have justled the greater number of the former out of that place.}}\n##* {{RQ:Austen Emma|volume=I|chapter=IX|pages=184–185|pageref="
  body "185|passage=I have so often heard Mr. Woodhouse recommend a baked '''apple'''. I believe it is the only way that Mr. Woodhouse thinks the fruit thoroughly wholesome. We have '''apple''' dumplings, how"
  body "ever, very often. Patty makes an excellent '''apple'''-dumpling.}}\n##* {{RQ:Lawrence Phoenix|title=Flowery Tuscany|section=III|page=52|passage=This red seems to me the perfect premonition of summer—l"
  body "ike the red on the outside of '''apple''' blossom—and later, the red of the '''apple'''. It is the premonition in redness of summer and of autumn.}}\n##* {{RQ:Guardian|date=28 October 2013|author=John"
  body " Vallins|title=Apples of Concord|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20230923080841/https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2013/oct/28/somerset-apples-of-concord|passage=Close by and under cover, "
  body "I watched the juicing process. '''Apples''' were washed, then tipped, stalks and all, into the crusher and reduced to pulp.}}\n## ''Often with a [[qualify]]ing [[word#Noun|word]]'': any fruit or [[veg"
  body "etable#Noun|vegetable]], or any other [[thing]] (such as a [[cone#Noun|cone]] or [[gall#Noun|gall]]) produced by a [[plant#Noun|plant]], especially if from a tree and similar to the fruit of {{taxfmt|"
  body "Malus domestica|species}} ''({{senseno|en|Q89}})''. {{defdate|from 9th c.}}\n##: {{coi|en|[[custard apple|custard '''apple''']]&emsp;&emsp;&emsp; [[rose apple|rose '''apple''']]&emsp;&emsp;&emsp; [[th"
  body "orn apple|thorn '''apple''']]}}\n##* {{RQ:d'Anghiera Eden Newe Worlde|chapter=Weste Indies|subchapter=Of Venemous Apples wherwith They Poyson Theyr Arrowes|folio=198|verso=1|passage=The '''apples''' w"
  body "herewith the Indian Canibales inueneme theyr arrowes, growe on certeyne trees couered with many braunches and leaues beinge very greene and growyng thicke. They are laden with abundaunce of theſe euyl"
  body "l frutes, {{...}}}}\n##* {{RQ:Gerard Herball|chapter=Of the Pine Tree|page=1174|passage=This '''apple''' is called in high Dutch, Zyꝛbel {{quote-gloss|Zyrbel}}: in low Dutch, Pijn appel: in Engliſh, P"
  body "ine apple, Clogge, and Cone. {{...}} The vvhole Cone or '''apple''' being boiled vvith freſh Horehound, ſaith ''{{w|Galen}}'', and aftervvards boyled againe vvith a little hony till the decoction be c"
  body "ome to the thicknes of hony, maketh an excellent medicine for the clenſing of the cheſt and lungs.}}\n##* {{RQ:Pliny Holland Historie of the World|tome=1|book=XI|chapter=The Trees of the Iland Tyles w"
  body "ithin the Persian Sea. Moreover, of Those Trees that Beare Woll or Cotton.|page=364|passage=As touching Arabia, vvhich lyeth neere and bordereth upon theſe Iſlands, the ſpices and odoriferous fruits t"
  body "hat be therein, are to be treated of vvith diſtinction: for their merchandiſe doth conſiſt of roots, braunches, barke, juice or liquor, gums and roſins, vvood, tvvigs, flovvers, leaves, and '''apple''"
  body "'.}}\n##* {{RQ:Topsell Foure-footed Beastes|chapter=IX|page=666|passage=The fruite or '''Apples''' of Palme-trees (eſpecially ſuch as grovv in ſalt grounds neare the Sea ſides, as in ''Cyrene'' of ''A"
  body "ffrica'', and ''Indea'', and not in ''Egypt'', ''Cyprus'', ''Syria'', ''Helvetia'', and ''Aſsiria'' do fatten and feed Hogges.}}\n##* {{quote-book|en|year=1658|author=John Baptista Porta [''i.e.'', {{"
  body "w|Giambattista della Porta}}]|chapter=That the Countries and Places where Simples Grow, are Chiefly to be Considered|translator=[anonymous]|title=[[w:Magia Naturalis|Natural Magick {{...|by John Bapti"
  body "sta Porta, a Neopolitane. In Twenty Books [...]}} Wherein are Set Forth All the Riches and Delights of the Natural Sciences]]|location=London|publisher={{...|Printed for}} John Wright,{{nb...|next to "
  body "the sign of the Globe in Little-Britain.}}|year_published=1669|section=1st book (Wherein are Searched Out the Causes of Things which Produce Wonderful Effects)|page=21|pageurl=https://books.google.com"
  body "/books?id=WddkXA6n51UC&pg=PA21|oclc=458053876|passage=In Perſia there grovvs a deadly tree, vvhoſe '''apples''' are poiſon, and preſent death: therefore there it is uſed for a puniſhment: but being br"
  body "ought over to the Kings into Egypt, they become vvholeſome '''apples''' to eat, and loſe their harmfulneſſe, as ''{{w|Columella}}'' vvrites.}}\n##* {{quote-book|en|year=1768|author=Edward Search [pseu"
  body "donym; {{w|Abraham Tucker}}]|chapter=External Nature|title=The Light of Nature Pursued|location=London|publisher={{...|Printed by}} T. Jones,{{nb...|in Fetter-Lane}}; and sold by [[w:Thomas Payne|T[ho"
  body "mas] Payne]],{{nb...|at the Mews-Gate.}}|volume=!II, part I (Theology)|section=paragraph 13|page=302|pageurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=U_5NAQAAIAAJ&pg=PA302|oclc=1326256104|passage=[T]he fly i"
  body "njects her juices into the oak leaf to raiſe an '''apple''' for hatching her young and therein ſupplies us vvith ink for our correſpondence and improvement.}}\n##* {{RQ:Cook King Voyage|volume=II|chap"
  body "ter=IX|page=174|passage=[I]t {{quote-gloss|Otaheite}} is remarkable for producing great quantities of that delicious fruit we called '''apples''', which are found in none of the others, except Eimeo.}"
  body "}\n##* {{quote-book|en|year=1825|author=w:Theodric Romeyn Beck; William Dunlop|title=Elements of Medical Jurisprudence.{{nb...|[...] Second Edition, with Notes, and an Appendix of Original Cases and t"
  body "he Latest Discoveries. By William Dunlop, Member of the Royal College of Surgeons, London; of the Medico-Chirurgical, and of the Wernerian Society of Natural History, Edinburgh; and Lecturer on Medica"
  body "l Jurisprudence, &c. &c.}}|edition=2nd|location=London|publisher={{...|Printed for}} John Anderson,{{nb...|medical bookseller, West-Smithfield}}|page=565|oclc=1012791003|passage=''Hippomane mancinella"
  body ".'' (Manchineel-tree.) Dr. Peysonnel relates that a soldier, who was a slave with the Turks, eat some of the '''apples''' of this tree, and was soon seized with a swelling and pain of the abdomen.}}\n"
  body "##* {{quote-book|en|year=1829|author=&#91;{{w|John Leonard Knapp}}&#93;|title=The Journal of a Naturalist|edition=2nd|location=London|publisher=[[w:John Murray (publishing house)|John Murray]],{{nb..."
  body "|Albemarle-Street.}}|pages=250–251|pageurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=9XdJAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA250|oclc=17661598|passage=The cross-bill will have seeds from the '''apple''', or cone of the fir—the gre"
  body "en-finch, seeds from the uplands, or door of barn, or rickyard.}}\n##* {{quote-book|en|year=1833|author=Charles Williams|chapter=The Aged Tree|title=The Vegetable World|location=London|publisher=Frede"
  body "rick Westley and [[w:Abraham Hopkins Davis|A[braham] H[opkins] Davis]],{{nb...|Stationers’-Hall Court.}}|page=192|pageurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=_6RgAAAAcAAJ&pg=PA192|oclc=18038938|passage="
  body "One kind of '''apple''' or gall, inhabited only by one grub, is hard and woody on the outside, resembling a little wooden ball, of a yellowish color, but internally it is of a soft, spongy texture.}}\"
  body "n##* {{quote-journal|en|year=1889|author=B. D. Halstead<!--See p. 336-->|title=Report of the Section of Vegetable Pathology [9.—Apple Rusts.]|journal=Report of the [[w:United States Secretary of Agric"
  body "ulture|Commissioner of Agriculture]]. 1888|location=Washington, D.C.|publisher=[[w:United States Government Publishing Office|Government Printing Office]]|page=376|pageurl=https://books.google.com/boo"
  body "ks?id=0hVFAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA376|oclc=942757499|passage=The \""'''apple'''\"" or gall usually forms a somewhat kidney-shaped excrescence, attached by a small base on the concave side, and varying in size fro"
  body "m a half an inch to an inch and a half in length.}}\n## Something which [[resemble]]s the fruit of {{taxfmt|Malus domestica|species}} ''({{senseno|en|Q89}})'' in [[shape#Noun|shape]] (such as a [[ball"
  body "#Noun|ball]], [[breast#Noun|breast]], or [[globe#Noun|globe]]) or [[color#Noun|colour]].\n##* {{RQ:Pliny Holland Historie of the World|tome=2|book=XXXVI|chapter=The First Invention of Glasse, and the "
  body "Manner of Making It. Of a Kind of Glasse, Called Obsidianum. Also of Sundrie Kinds of Glasse, and Those of Manie Formes.|page=598|passage=[H]old a round ball or hollovv '''apple''' of glaſſe full of v"
  body "vater againſt the Sunne, it vvill be ſo hot, that it is ready to burne any cloth that it toucheth.}}\n##* {{quote-book|en|year=1705|author=J. S.|chapter=The Ways and Artifices of a Town-jilt, &c.|titl"
  body "e=City and Country Recreation: Or, Wit and Merriment Rightly Calculated, for the Pleasure and Advantage of Either Sex.{{nb...|In Two Parts. [...] To which is Added, The Misery of Gaming: Or The Art of"
  body " Keeping Ready Money in One’s Pocket at All Times: With Other Useful Matters, never before Made Publick.}}|location=London|publisher={{...|Printed by}} W. O. for P. Parker,{{nb...|at the Leg and Star "
  body "in Cornhil}}|section=2nd part|page=104|pageurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=R7lcAAAAcAAJ&pg=PA104|oclc=1325795882|passage=[S]hrugging up her Shoulders, to ſhevv the tempting '''Apples''' of her v"
  body "vhite Breaſts, ſhe ſuddainly lets them ſink again, to hide them, bluſhing, as if this had been done by chance, {{...}}}}\n##* {{quote-book|en|year=1761|chapter=Of the Order of the Procession of the El"
  body "ectoral Princes, and of Those who are to Carry the Honorary Ensigns|title=The Modern Part of an Universal History, from the Earliest Account of Time.{{nb...|Compiled from Original Writers. By the Auth"
  body "ors of the Antient Part.}}|location=London|publisher={{...|Printed for}} [[w:Samuel Richardson|S[amuel] Richardson]],{{nb...|T[homas] Osborne, C. Hitch, A[ndrew] Millar, John Rivington, S. Crowder, B."
  body " Law and Co. T[homas] Longman and C. Ware.}}|volume=XXX|page=508|pageurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=ONjh-Aat5ZYC&pg=PA508|oclc=1180917051|passage=[T]he ſaid elector of ''Saxony'' ſhall have on "
  body "his right the count-palatine of the ''Rhine'', vvho ſhall carry the globe or imperial '''apple'''; and, on his left, the marquis of ''Brandenburg'' carrying the ſcepter.}}\n##* {{quote-book|en|year=18"
  body "07|author=w:Sharon Turner|chapter=The Political State of Norway, Sweden, and Denmark, in the Eighth Century|title=The History of the Anglo-Saxons.{{nb...|[...] Second Edition, Corrected and Enlarged.}"
  body "}|edition=2nd|location=London|publisher={{...|Printed for}} [[w:Longman|Longman, Hurst, Rees, & Orme]],{{nb...|Paternoster Row.}}|volume=I|section=book III, footnote 20|page=200|pageurl=https://books."
  body "google.com/books?id=O2AOAAAAQAAJ&pg=PA200|column=2|oclc=1018396940|passage=The arms of Upland were a golden '''apple''', or globe, surrounded with a belt, in allusion to the monarchy.}}\n##* {{quote-b"
  body "ook|en|year=1956|author=w:Marion Hargrove|title=The Girl He Left Behind: Or, All Quiet in the Third Platoon|location=New York, N.Y.|publisher=w:Viking Books|page=129|oclc=1336143924|passage=Andy picke"
  body "d up his two grenades and followed the line into the pits. The '''apples''' felt strangely heavy in his hands, and when he looked at them one was as ugly and lethal-looking as the other.}}\n##* {{quot"
  body "e-book|en|year=1975|author=[[w:C. W. Smith (writer)|C[harles] W[illiam] Smith]]|chapter=IX|title=Country Music|location=New York, N.Y.|publisher=w:Farrar, Straus and Giroux|page=256|isbn=978-0-374-130"
  body "30-5|passage=A peasant blouse that showed the tops of those lovely little '''apples'''.}}\n##* {{quote-book|en|year=2008|author=w:Harald Kleinschmidt|title=Ruling the Waves: Emperor Maximilian I, the "
  body "Search for Islands and the Transformation of the European World Picture c. 1500|series=Bibliotheca Humanistica & Reformatorica|seriesvolume=63|location=’t Goy, Houten, Utrecht|publisher=Hes & de Graaf"
  body " Publishers|page=79|isbn=978-90-6194-020-3|issn=1567-8385|passage=Contrary to [[w:Henricus Martellus Germanus|Henricus Martellus {{quote-gloss|Germanus}}]], [[w:Martin Behaim|{{quote-gloss|Martin}} Be"
  body "haim]] included the tropics {{quote-gloss|on his globe}}. {{...}} Evidently, there was no space for a Fourth Continent on Behaim's '''apple''', although some recollection of the Catalan map seems to l"
  body "ie behind the shape of southern Africa.}}\n### {{ellipsis of|en|Adam's apple|t=the lump in the throat, usually more [[noticeable]] in men than in women; the [[laryngeal prominence]]}}.\n###* {{quote-b"
  body "ook|en|year=1898|author=[[w:Hugh Clifford (colonial administrator)|Hugh [Charles] Clifford]]|chapter=In Arcadia|title=Studies in Brown Humanity: Being Scrawls and Smudges in Sepia, White, and Yellow|l"
  body "ocation=London|publisher=[[w:Grant Richards (publisher)|Grant Richards]]{{nb...|9 Henrietta Street, Covent Garden, W.C.}}|page=99|pageurl=https://archive.org/details/studiesinbrownhu00clif/page/99/mod"
  body "e/1up|oclc=2059083|passage=The sweat of fear and exertion was streaming down his face and chest, and his breath came in short, tearing, hard-drawn gasps and gulps, while the '''apple''' in his throat "
  body "leaped up and down ceaselessly like a ball balanced on a dancing jet of water.}}\n###* {{RQ:Williamson Dandelion Days|chapter=Formation of the Owl Club|pages=113–114|pageref=113|passage=Elsie went awa"
  body "y with her parents to Belgium and the convent-school on the twelfth, and as they left The Firs in the battered station cab surrounded by boxes and trunks, Willie could not speak. The '''apple''' in hi"
  body "s throat rose and remained there.}}\n###* {{RQ:Joyce Ulysses|page=234|passage=He looked with vague hope up and down the quay, a big '''apple''' bulging in his neck.}}\n###* {{quote-book|en|year=a. '''"
  body "1985''' (date written)<!--year after author's death-->|author=[[w:Liam O'Flaherty|Liam O’Flaherty]]|chapter=Josephine|editor=A[ngeline] A. Kelly|title=The Collected Stories|volume=1|location=New York,"
  body " N.Y.|publisher=w:Palgrave Macmillan|year_published=1999|page=131|pageurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=YbUYDAAAQBAJ&pg=PA131|isbn=978-1-349-62699-1|passage=The '''apple''' in his neck was hitting"
  body " against his collar every time he drew breath and he tore at his collar nervously.}}\n###* {{RQ:Martin Storm of Swords|page=846|passage=If the Hound had not been moving, the knife might have cored the"
  body " '''apple''' of his throat; instead it only grazed his ribs, and wound up quivering in the wall near the door. He laughed then, a laugh as cold and hollow as if it had come from the bottom of a deep w"
  body "ell.}}\n###* {{quote-book|en|year=2003|author=[[w:Sandra Benitez|Sandra Benítez]]|chapter=|title=Night of the Radishes|location=New York, N.Y.|publisher=[[w:Hachette Books|Hyperion]]|page=223|pageurl="
  body "https://archive.org/details/nightofradishes00ben/page/223/mode/1up|isbn=978-0-7868-6400-3|passage=The '''apple''' in his neck bobbles as he gulps. “You've got to be kidding.” / “No, I'm not. Your inhe"
  body "ritance amounts to maybe three hundred thousand dollars.\""}}\n### {{ellipsis of|en|apple-green|t=a bright green colour with a light tint of yellow, like that of a [[Granny Smith]] apple}}.\n###: {{col"
  body "or panel|7FD700}}\n### {{lb|en|historical}} {{ellipsis of|en|apple of the eye|t=the [[pupil]], or pupil and iris, of the eye, originally [[believe]]d to be [[spherical]]; also, the eyeball}}.\n###* {{"
  body "RQ:Pliny Holland Historie of the World|tome=1|book=XI|chapter=A Discourse Anatomicall, of the Nature of Living Creatures, Part by Part, according to Their Particular Members|page=334|passage=None have"
  body " their eies all of one colour: for the ball or '''apple''' in the middeſt is ordinarily of another colour than the vvhite about it.}}\n###* {{RQ:Homer Chapman Iliads|book=XIV|pages=197–198|pageref=198"
  body "|passage=The dart did vndergore / His eye-lid, by his eyes deare rootes; and out the '''apple''' fell, / The eye pierc'd through: {{...}}}}\n### {{lb|en|informal}} The round, [[fleshy]] [[part#Noun|pa"
  body "rt]] of a [[cheek#Noun|cheek]] between the eye and the [[corner#Noun|corner]] of the [[mouth#Noun|mouth]] when a [[person#Noun|person]] is [[smile#Verb|smiling]].\n### {{senseid|en|geometry}}{{lb|en|g"
  body "eometry}} The [[surface of revolution]] of a [[circular arc]] of an [[angle#Noun|angle]] [[great#Adjective|greater]] than 180° [[rotate#Verb|rotated]] about the [[straight line]] [[pass#Verb|passing]]"
  body " through the [[arc#Noun|arc]]'s two [[endpoint]]s.\n###: {{cot|en|{{l|en|lemon|id=geometry}}}}\n### {{lb|en|smoking}} ''In full'' '''apple bowl''': a round [[bowl#Noun|bowl]] of a [[tobacco pipe]]; al"
  body "so, a tobacco pipe with such a bowl.\n### {{lb|en|obsolete|baseball|slang}} ''In full'' '''old apple''': a [[baseball]]. {{defdate|from 20th c.}}\n###* {{quote-av|en|date=25 February 1990|writers=w:Ma"
  body "tt Groening; w:Al Jean; w:Mike Reiss; w:Sam Simon|episode=w:The Telltale Head|title=w:The Simpsons|season=1|number=8|passage=Hey Dad! What do you say we toss the old '''apple''' around, huh? Sound lik"
  body "e fun?}}\n## {{senseid|en|forbidden fruit}}{{lb|en|Christianity}} According to [[postbiblical]] [[Christian#Adjective|Christian]] [[tradition#Noun|tradition]], the fruit of the [[tree of knowledge]] w"
  body "hich was [[eat#Verb|eaten]] by [[Adam and Eve]] despite [[God]] [[command#Verb|commanding]] them not to do so; the [[forbidden fruit]]. {{defdate|from 11th c.}}\n##* {{RQ:Milton Paradise Lost|book=IX|"
  body "sig=&#91;Ll4&#93;|page=272|lines=485–487|passage=Him {{quote-gloss|man}} by fraud I {{quote-gloss|{{w|Satan}}}} have ſeduc'd / From his Creator, and the more to increaſe / Your vvonder, vvith an '''Ap"
  body "ple'''; {{...}}}}\n##* {{RQ:Mary Shelley Frankenstein|volume=III|page=102|passage=I read and re-read her letter, and some softened feelings stole into my heart, and dared to whisper paradisiacal dream"
  body "s of love and joy; but the '''apple''' was already eaten, and the angel's arm bared to drive me from all hope.}}\n##* {{RQ:Southey All for Love|page=20|passage=Yes, of all human follies, love, / Methi"
  body "nks, hath served me best. / The '''Apple''' had done but little for me / If {{w|Eve}} had not done the rest.}}\n##* {{RQ:Stowe My Wife and I|chapter=Congratulations, etc.|page=399|passage=Yes, fair Ev"
  body "e, just as {{w|Adam}} ate the '''apple''', so beware!}}\n##* {{quote-book|en|year='''1975''' (date written)|author=w:Barry Reckord|chapter=White Witch|chapterurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=84oH"
  body "EAAAQBAJ&pg=PT209|title=For the Reckord: A Collection of Three Plays|location=London|publisher=w:Oberon Books|year_published=2010|isbn=978-1-84943-053-1|passage=Yes mam. Woman ate the '''apple''', and"
  body " discovered sex, and lost all shame, and lift{{sic}} up her fig-leaf, and she must suffer the pains of hell. Monthly.}}\n##* {{quote-song|en|year=1976|author=w:Joni Mitchell|title=Song for Sharon|albu"
  body "m=[[w:Hejira (album)|Hejira]]|location=Los Angeles, Calif.|publisher=w:Asylum Records|oclc=939485378|passage=Sharon you've got a husband / And a family and a farm / I've got the '''apple''' of temptat"
  body "ion / And a diamond snake around my arm}}\n## {{lb|en|obsolete|botany}} {{synonym of|en|pome|t=a [[type#Noun|type]] of fruit in which the often [[edible#Adjective|edible]] [[flesh#Noun|flesh]] [[arise"
  body "#Verb|arises]] from the [[swollen#Adjective|swollen]] [[base#Noun|base]] of the [[flower#Noun|flower]] and not from the [[carpel]]s}}.\n## {{lb|en|internet slang|humorous}} An imaginary [[diminutive]]"
  body " unit of [[height]].\n##: {{ux|en|He's only three '''apples''' tall}}\n# {{senseid|en|apple tree}} A tree of the genus ''Malus''; especially {{taxfmt|Malus domestica|species}} which is cultivated for "
  body "its edible fruit; the [[apple tree]]. {{defdate|from 15th c.}}\n#: {{synonyms|en|malus}}\n#* {{RQ:Bacon Sylva Sylvarum|chapter=Experiments in Consort, Touching the Lasting of Herbs and Trees|page=146|"
  body "para=584|passage=''Trees'' that beare ''Maſt'', and ''Nuts'', are commonly more laſting, than thoſe that beare ''Fruits''; Eſpecially the ''Moiſter Fruits'': As ''Oakes'', ''Beeches'', ''Cheſ-nuts'', "
  body "''VVall-nuts'', ''Almonds'', ''Pine-Trees'', &c. laſt longer than '''''Apples''''', ''Peares'', ''Plums'', &c.}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=1913|chapter=The Science of Plant Growing|editor=John Weathers"
  body "|title=Commercial Gardening{{nb...|A Practical & Scientific Treatise for Market Gardeners, Market Growers, Fruit Flower & Vegetable Growers, Nurserymen etc. [...] In Four Volumes: Fully Illustrated}}|"
  body "location=London|publisher=The Gresham Publishing Company{{nb...|34–35 Southampton Street Strand London}}|volume=I|section=§4 (The Root and Its Work)|page=38|pageurl=https://archive.org/details/commerc"
  body "ialgarden0001john/page/38/mode/1up|oclc=2485680|passage=If the grafted portion of an '''Apple''' or other tree were examined after one hundred years, the old cut surfaces would still be present, for m"
  body "ature or ripened wood, being dead, never unites.}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=2000|author=Peter Thomas|chapter=The Next Generation: New Trees from Old|title=Trees: Their Natural History|location=Cambrid"
  body "ge, Cambridgeshire|publisher=w:Cambridge University Press|year_published=2001|page=227|pageurl=https://archive.org/details/treestheirnatura0000thom_s4l2/page/227/mode/1up|isbn=978-0-521-45351-6|passag"
  body "e=This allows a weak plant to benefit from the strong roots of another, or a vigorous tree (such as an '''apple''') to be kept small by growing on 'dwarfing rootstock'.}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=2009"
  body "|author=Sid Gardner|title=The Faults of the Owens Valley|location=Bloomington, Ind.|publisher=w:iUniverse|page=34|pageurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=gcbQzBOnc0YC&pg=PA34|isbn=978-1-4401-7793-4|"
  body "passage=Used to be apple orchards, used to be the river and irrigation ditches that watered the '''apples''', used to be mining towns.}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=2012|author=Terri Reid|chapter=Startin"
  body "g an Orchard|title=The Everything Guide to Living Off the Grid: A Back-to-basics Manual for Independent Living|series=Everything Series|location=Avon, Mass.|publisher=Adams Media, [[w:F+W|F+W Media]]|"
  body "page=77|pageurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=rQrtDQAAQBAJ&pg=PT78|isbn=978-1-4405-1275-9|passage=Some fruit trees, like plums, do well in damp soil conditions. Other fruit trees, like '''apples''"
  body "', need well-drained soil.}}\n# {{synonym of|en|applewood|t=the [[wood#Noun|wood]] of the [[apple tree]]}}. {{defdate|from 19th c.}}\n# {{lb|en|puristic|otherwise|obsolete}} A fruit of any kind.\n# {{"
  body "lb|en|by extension|slang}}\n## {{lb|en|often|with qualifying word}} A [[person]].\n##* {{quote-book|en|year=1928|year_published=1984|author=S.J. Perelman|chapter=Phantoms of the Dawn|title=That Old ga"
  body "ng o' Mine: The Early and Essential S.J. Perelman|page=43|text=“I saw a little guy with a can opener fooling around that gum machine,” was the reply.<br />“And then?” asked McGonigle.<br />“I can’t sa"
  body "y,” replied the poor '''apple'''.|pageurl=https://archive.org/details/thatoldgangomine00pere/page/43/}}\n##* {{quote-journal|en|year=1948|month=April|author=John C. Ropke|title=You Can’t Stay On Top|j"
  body "ournal=Masked Rider Western|page=64|text=“Take it easy with Thompson, Eddie,” he said lazily. “He’s a good '''apple''' but he’s mighty tough to go pushing around. He’s had a lot of bad luck lately.”|p"
  body "ageurl=https://archive.org/details/masked-rider-western-v-23-n-03-1948-04/page/64/}}\n##* {{quote-book|en|year=1963|author=H.E. Bates|title=Oh! To Be in England|page=20|text=Pop delighted in calling h"
  body "is grandson Blenheim; it was such a nice round apple of a name.<br />‘Well, how’s Charley boy? And how’s my little '''apple'''?’|pageurl=https://archive.org/details/ohtobeinengland0000heba/page/20/}}\"
  body "n## {{lb|en|amateur radio}} {{synonym of|en|CBer|t=a [[CB radio]] [[enthusiast]]}}.\n##* {{quote-journal|en|year=1977|author=|title=|editor=w:Bernard Dixon|journal=w:New Scientist|location=London|publ"
  body "isher=[[w:TI Media#International Publishing Corporation|IPC Magazines]]|volume=74|page=764|column=1|passage=Because of overcrowding, many a CB enthusiast (called an \""'''apple'''\"") is strapping an il"
  body "legal linear amplifier (\""boots\"") on to his transceiver (\""ears\"") which is limited by the Federal Communications Commission (\""Big Daddy\"" in the US) to an output power of no more than five watts.}}"
  body "\n## {{lb|en|ice hockey}} An [[assist#Noun|assist]].\n## {{lb|en|US|derogatory|ethnic slur}} A [[Native American#Adjective|Native American]] or [[redskinned]] person who [[act#Verb|acts]] or [[think#V"
  body "erb|thinks]] like a [[white#Adjective|white]] ([[Caucasian#Adjective|Caucasian]]) person.\n##: {{coordinate terms|en|banana|coconut|Oreo|Twinkie}}\n##* {{quote-book|en|year=1996|author=w:Joel Spring|c"
  body "hapter=From Thomas Jefferson to Henry Ford: The End of the Choctaw Republic|chapterurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=APEvisJqs1oC&pg=PT214|title=The Cultural Transformation of A Native American Fa"
  body "mily and Its Tribe 1763–1995: A Basket of Apples|location=Abingdon, Oxfordshire&#59; New York, N.Y.|publisher=w:Routledge|year_published=2011|section=part II (The Choctaw Republic and Its People)|doi="
  body "10.4324/9780203053614|isbn=978-0-8058-2303-5|passage=My ancestors five generations removed were \""'''apples'''\"" who were \""White\"" on the inside and \""Red\"" on the outside. {{...}} We need a new bree"
  body "d of \""'''apples'''.\""}}\n##* {{quote-book|en|year=1998|author=w:Opal J. Moore|chapter=‘From the Back of the Bus to the Back of the National Priority List’: The Civil Rights Movement, Integration, and"
  body " beyond [Git that Gal a Red Dress: A Conversation Between Female Faculty at a State School in Virginia]|editor=w:Daryl Cumber Dance|title=Honey, Hush! An Anthology of African American Women’s Humor|lo"
  body "cation=New York, N.Y.|publisher=[[w:W. W. Norton & Company|W[illiam] W[arder] Norton & Company]]|page=537|pageurl=https://archive.org/details/honeyhush00dary/page/537/mode/1up|isbn=978-0-393-04557-4|p"
  body "assage=The presenter, close to tears, told the audience that she's really an '''apple'''—white on the inside and red on the outside—Native American.}}\n\n====Hyponyms====\n{{col2|en|title=fruit of the"
  body " genus ''Malus''\n|{{vern|cherry apple}} ({{taxfmt|Malus baccata|species}})|cooking apple|[[crab apple]], [[crabapple]] ({{taxfmt|Malus|genus}} spp.)\n|{{vern|dessert apple}}\n|eating apple\n|{{vern|w"
  body "ild apple}} ({{taxfmt|Malus|genus}} spp.)|wine apple\n}}\n\n====Derived terms====\n{{col3|en\n| a bad tree does not yield good apples|acid of apples|Adam's apple|African custard apple|alley apple|[[al"
  body "ligator apple]] ({{taxlink|Annona glabra|species}})|American as apple pie|an apple a day,an apple a day keeps the doctor away,an apple a day keeps the doctor at bay|antiapple|applanche\n| Apple|applea"
