  body "nas}}\n* Tahitian: {{tt|ty|'āpara}}\n* Tajik: {{tt+|tg|себ}}\n* Talysh: {{t|tly|sef}}, {{tt|tly|سیف|tr=sif}} {{qualifier|Asalemi}}\n* Tamil: {{tt+|ta|ஆப்பிள்}}, {{t+|ta|குமளி}}, {{t+|ta|அரத்தி}}\n* Ta"
  body "rantino: {{tt|roa-tar|mulèdde|f}}\n* Taroko: {{tt|trv|ringgo}} {{q|Tgdaya}}, {{tt|trv|supaw}} {{q|Truku}}\n* Tat: {{t|ttt|sib}}, {{tt|ttt|сиб}}\n* Tatar: {{tt+|tt|алма}}\n* Telugu: {{tt+|te|కాయ}}, {{t"
  body "t+|te|ఆపిల్}}\n* Tetum: {{tt|tet|masán}}\n* Thai: {{tt+|th|แอปเปิล}}\n* Tibetan: {{tt|bo|ཀུ་ཤུ}}\n* Tigrinya: {{tt|ti|ቱፋሕ}}, {{tt|ti|ሜለ}}\n* Tlingit: {{tt|tli|x'áax'}}\n* Tokelauan: {{t|tkl|apu}}\n* T"
  body "ongan: {{t|to|'apele}}\n* Tsonga: {{tt|ts|vundzu}}\n* Tsou: {{tt|tsu|heesi}}\n* Turkish: {{tt+|tr|elma}}, {{tt|tr|tüffah}}\n*: Ottoman Turkish: {{tt|ota|الما|tr=elma}}, {{tt|ota|سیب|tr=sib}}\n* Turkme"
  body "n: {{tt+|tk|alma}}\n* Udi: {{tt|udi|еъшӏ}}\n* Udmurt: {{tt|udm|улмо}}, {{tt|udm|яблок}}\n* Ugaritic: {{tt|uga|𐎚𐎔𐎈}}\n* Ukrainian: {{tt+|uk|я́блуко|n}}\n* Unami: {{tt|unm|apëlìsh}}\n* Urdu: {{tt|ur|سیب"
  body "|m}}\n* Uyghur: {{tt+|ug|ئالما}}\n* Uzbek: {{tt+|uz|olma}}\n* Venda: {{tt|ve|apula}}\n* Venetan: {{tt+|vec|pomo}}\n* Vietnamese: {{tt+|vi|táo tây}}, {{tt+|vi|bôm}}, {{tt+|vi|táo}}, {{tt+|vi|bom}}\n* V"
  body "ilamovian: {{tt|wym|epuł|m}}\n* Volapük: {{tt+|vo|pod}}, {{qualifier|older term|obsolete}} {{tt|vo|apod}}\n* Võro: {{tt|vro|upin}}\n* Walloon: {{tt+|wa|peme}}\n* Waray-Waray: {{tt|war|mansanas}}\n* We"
  body "lsh: {{tt+|cy|afal}}\n* Winnebago: {{t|win|kšee}}\n* Wolof: {{tt|wo|pom}}\n* Xhosa: {{tt|xh|iapile|c5|c6}}\n* Yaghnobi: {{tt|yai|себ}}\n* Yakut: {{tt|sah|яблоко}}, {{tt|sah|дьаабылака}}\n* Yiddish: {{"
  body "tt|yi|עפּל|m}}\n* Yoruba: {{tt|yo|ápù}}\n* Yucatec Maya: {{tt|yua|chak pakʼaal|alt=chak pakʼáal}}\n* Yup'ik: {{tt|esu|atsarpak}}\n* Yurok: {{tt|yur|ˀɹplɹs}}\n* Zazaki: {{tt+|zza|saye|f}}, {{tt|zza|ša|"
  body "f}}\n* Zhuang: {{tt|za|makbinzgoj}}, {{tt|za|makbingzgoj}}\n* Zulu: {{tt+|zu|ihhabhula|c5|c6}}\n* Zuni: {{tt|zun|mansana}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{trans-top|anything produced by a plant, especially if "
  body "from a tree and similar to the fruit of ''Malus domestica''}}\n* Finnish: {{t+|fi|hedelmä}}\n* Galician: {{t-needed|gl}}\n* Tamil: {{t+|ta|பழம்}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{trans-top|something which resem"
  body "bles the fruit of ''Malus domestica''}}\n* Finnish: {{t+|fi|omena}}\n* Galician: {{t-needed|gl}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{trans-see|Adam's apple}}\n\n{{trans-see|apple-green}}\n\n{{trans-see|apple of th"
  body "e eye}}\n\n{{trans-top|round, fleshy part of a cheek}}\n* Finnish: {{t+|fi|poskipää}}\n* Galician: {{t-needed|gl}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{trans-top|geometry: surface of revolution}}\n* Finnish: {{t+|f"
  body "i|omena}}\n* Galician: {{t-needed|gl}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{trans-top|round bowl of a tobacco pipe; tobacco pipe with such a bowl}}\n* Finnish: {{t|fi|[[pyöreä]] [[pesä]]}}\n* Galician: {{t-needed|g"
  body "l}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{trans-see|fruit of the tree of knowledge|forbidden fruit}}\n\n{{trans-see|tree of the genus ''Malus''|apple tree}}\n\n{{trans-see|wood of the apple tree|applewood}}\n}}\n\n="
  body "===See also====\n* {{l|en|malic}}\n\n===Verb===\n{{en-verb}}\n\n# {{lb|en|transitive}} To [[make#Verb|make]] (something) [[appear]] like an [[apple#Noun|apple]] ''({{senseno|en|Q89}})''.\n#* {{quote-b"
  body "ook|en|year=1992|author=w:Marilyn Strathern|chapter=Enterprising Kinship: Consumer Choice and the New Reproductive Technologies|title=Reproducing the Future: Essays on Anthropology, Kinship and the Ne"
  body "w Reproductive Technologies|location=Manchester|publisher=w:Manchester University Press|section=part I|page=38|pageurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=BM9RAQAAIAAJ&pg=PA38|isbn=978-0-7190-3673-6|pas"
  body "sage=To choose responsibly, our active citizen must know what is being offered, much of this knowledge being filtered through appearance: things must look what they are supposed to be. Apples must loo"
  body "k like applies. One might say they have to be '''appled'''-up; varieties are selected for marketing which have the most apple-like qualities.}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=2007|author=Claudia D. Newcorn|"
  body "chapter=4|title=Crossover|series=Chronicles of Feyree|seriesvolume=scroll 1|location=[United States]|publisher=Theogony Books|year_published=2021|page=35|chapterurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=c"
  body "dMnEAAAQBAJ&pg=PT62|isbn=978-1-942936-65-7|passage=A large smile '''appled''' his full cheeks as the four sprytes eagerly served themselves from the seeds and thinly sliced fruits.}}\n# {{lb|en|intran"
  body "sitive}}\n## To [[become]] like an apple.\n##* {{quote-book|en|year=2003|author=w:Gregory David Roberts|chapter=1|chapterurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=5JaxSJlpGmAC&pg=PT37|title=[[w:Shantaram "
  body "(novel)|Shantaram]]|location=London|publisher=[[w:Hachette Book Group|Hachette Digital]]|year_published=2012|section=part 1|isbn=978-1-405-51697-6|passage=He glanced at me, his cheeks '''appled''' in "
  body "the impish grin I was learning to recognise as the clever under-side of his broad and gentle smile.}}\n##* {{quote-book|en|year=2011|author=Cynthia Robinson|chapter=10|title=The Barbary Dogs|series=A "
  body "[[w:Thomas Dunne Books|Thomas Dunne Book]]|location=New York, N.Y.|publisher=Minotaur Books, [[w:St. Martin's Press|St. Martin’s Publishing Group]]|page=57|pageurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=gG"
  body "n4TxwXmFUC&pg=PA57|isbn=978-0-312-55974-8|passage=She smiled, and her cheeks '''appled''' up and her teeth were big and flat and her mouth was wide and spacious like an open invitation.}}\n## {{lb|en|"
  body "UK|dialectal|rare}} To [[collect#Verb|collect]] [[fir-cone]]s.\n## {{lb|en|obsolete|except|UK|dialectal}} Of a [[flower#Noun|flower]] [[bud#Noun|bud]] or [[vegetable#Noun|vegetable]] (especially a [[r"
  body "oot vegetable]]): to [[grow]] into the [[shape#Noun|shape]] of an apple.\n##* {{RQ:Pliny Holland Historie of the World|tome=2|book=XXI|chapter=Of Carduus, and Ixine: Of Tribulus and Anchusa|page=98|pa"
  body "ssage=As for Scolymus {{quote-gloss|possibly type of artichoke?}}, it differeth from the reſt of theſe Thiſtles herein, That the root, if it be ſodden, it is good to be eaten: beſides, it hath a ſtrau"
  body "nge nature, for all the ſort of them during the Summer throughout, never reſt and give over, but either they floure, or they '''apple''', or els be readie to bring foorth fruit: {{...}}}}\n##* {{RQ:La"
  body " Quintinie Evelyn Gard'ner|chapter=Dictionary|entry=To ''Pome'' or ''Apple''|page=42|column=1|passage=To ''Pome'' or '''''Apple''''', is ſaid of the Heads of ''Artichokes'' vvhen they grovv round, and"
  body " full ſhaped as an Apple. It is ſaid alſo of ''Lettuce'', &c.|brackets=on}}\n##* {{quote-book|en|year=1759|author=[[w:James Justice (horticulturalist)|James Justice]]|chapter=November|title=The Britis"
  body "h Gardener’s Calendar,{{nb...|Chiefly Adapted to the Climate of North-Britain: Directing the Necessary Works in Every Month, in the Kitchen, Fruit and Pleasure Gardens, and in the Nursery, Green-house"
  body " and Stove. To which is Added, a Dissertation on Forest Trees, and a Catalogue of Seeds, Roots, &c. with the Names of the Months Annexed in which They Ought to be Sown.}}|location=Edinburgh|publisher="
  body "{{...|Printed for}} R. Fleming|page=307|pageurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=mETHzHAoxYQC&pg=PA307|oclc=228745868|passage=You may novv ſovv upon moderate hot-beds, a fevv of the ſmall ſalad ſeeds"
  body ", ſuch as VVhite Muſtard, Rape, Creſſes, and Cabbage Lettuces, and you may also ſovv upon other hot-beds, not to be drawn until they are pretty large and vvell '''appled''', Radiſhes and Turnips, obſe"
  body "rving to ſovv them very thin, that the plants may have room to ſvvell and grovv; {{...}}}}\n##* {{quote-book|en|year=1798|author=Charles Marshall|chapter=Section XV. Of Esculents.|title=An Introductio"
  body "n to the Knowledge and Practice of Gardening,{{nb...|[...] The Second Edition. Considerably Enlarged and Improved.}}|edition=2nd|location=London|publisher={{...|Printed by}} John Rider, for [[w:Riving"
  body "ton (publishers)|F[rancis] and C[harles] Rivington]],{{nb...|No. 62, St. Paul’s Church-yard, London.}}|page=251|pageurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=BfVeAAAAcAAJ&pg=PA251|oclc=1014223763|passage="
  body "The ''cabbage turnep'' is of tvvo kinds; one '''apples''' above ground, and the other in it.}}\n##* {{quote-book|en|year=1807|author=[[w:Thomas Potts (writer)|Thomas Potts]]|entry=TURNIPS|entryurl=htt"
  body "ps://books.google.com.sg/books?id=L3EhAQAAMAAJ&pg=PT225|title=The British Farmer’s Cyclopædia; or, Complete Agricultural Dictionary;{{nb...|including Every Science or Subject Dependant on, or Connecte"
  body "d with, Improved Modern Husbandry: With the Breeding, Feeding, and Management, of Live Stock; the Modern Art of Farriery, Cure of the Diseases of Dogs; the Management of Bees; the Culture of Fruit and"
  body " Forest Trees; of Cyder; of Malt Liquor, and Made Wines. Embellished with Forty-two Engravings.}}|location=London|publisher={{...|Printed by}} W. Flint,{{nb...|Old Bailey}}, for Scatcherd and Letterma"
  body "n,{{nb...|Ave-Maria-Lane}}, and M. Jones,{{nb...|No. 1, Paternoster-Row.}}|column=2|oclc=977411949|passage=Some, however, recommend that the seed collected from a few turnips thus transplanted, should"
  body " be preserved and sown in drills, in order to raise plants for see for the general crop, drawing out all such as are weak and improper, leaving only those that are strong and which take the lead; and "
  body "that when these have '''appled''' or formed bulbs, to again take out such as do not appear good and perfect, as by this means turnip seed may be procured, not only of a more vigorous nature, but which"
  body " is capable of vegetating with less moisture and which produces stronger and more hardy plants.}}\n\n====Derived terms====\n* {{l|en|appleing}}, {{l|en|appling|pos=noun}}\n\n====Translations====\n{{tr"
  body "ans-top|(''transitive'') to make (something) appear like an apple; (''intransitive'') to become like an apple}}\n* Finnish: {{t|fi|[[muuttaa]] [[omena]]n [[näköinen|näköiseksi]]}} {{qualifier|transiti"
  body "ve}}, {{t|fi|[[muuttua]] [[omena]]n [[näköinen|näköiseksi]]}} {{qualifier|intransitive}}\n* Galician: {{t-needed|gl}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{trans-top|to collect fir-cones}}\n* Finnish: {{t|fi|[[poimi"
  body "a]] [[käpy|käpyjä]]}}\n* Galician: {{t-needed|gl}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{trans-top|of a flower bud or vegetable: to grow into the shape of an apple}}\n* Finnish: {{t|fi|[[kasvaa]] [[omena]]n [[muotoi"
  body "nen|muotoiseksi]]}}\n* Galician: {{t-needed|gl}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n===Notes===\n<references group=\""n\""/>\n\n===References===\n<references/>\n\n===Further reading===\n* {{pedia}}\n* {{pedia|apple ("
  body "disambiguation)}}\n* {{R:Dictionary.com|pos=n}}\n* {{R:Online Etymology Dictionary}}\n\n===Anagrams===\n* {{anagrams|en|a=aelpp|pepla|appel|appel.|Appel}}\n\n{{C|en|Fruits|Greens|Colors|Mythological p"
  body "lants|Pome fruits|Rose family plants|Trees}}\n\n==Middle English==\n\n===Noun===\n{{head|enm|noun|altform=1}}\n\n# {{alt form|enm|appel}}""}}"

